{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-8b5070ccf7119971","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t                                             Contextual Semantic Relevance Tracks fMRI BOLD Responses\n2\t                                                      During Naturalistic Speech Comprehension\n3\t                                                                                  Kun Sun1 and Rong Wang2\n4\t\n5\t                                                                     Department of Linguistics, Tongji University ∗\n6\t                                                                      1\n7\t                                                           2\n8\t                                                             Department of Computational Linguistics, Tuebingen University †\n9\t\n10\t\n11\t\n12\t\n13\t                                                                                              Abstract\n14\t                                                       Naturalistic language comprehension requires listeners to process both local probabilistic\n15\tarXiv:2607.15856v1 [cs.CL] 17 Jul 2026\n16\t\n17\t\n18\t\n19\t\n20\t                                                   expectations and contextual semantic relations. Surprisal has been widely used to quantify lo-\n21\t                                                   cal word unexpectedness, but evidence that it robustly predicts fMRI BOLD responses during\n22\t                                                   continuous comprehension has been mixed. This study investigates whether contextual seman-\n23\t                                                   tic relevance, defined as how strongly an incoming word relates to its recent semantic context,\n24\t                                                   predicts BOLD responses during naturalistic speech comprehension. We analyzed two pub-\n25\t                                                   lic fMRI datasets, the Alice dataset and the Moth dataset, treating them as complementary\n26\t                                                   rather than identical replications. Transformed BOLD responses were modeled with generalized\n27\t                                                   additive mixed models (GAMMs) and original continuous BOLD time series were tested with\n28\t                                                   FIR/deconvolution analyses. In Alice, semantic relevance was significant across all 12 ROIs\n29\t                                                   (region of interest), whereas surprisal was not significant after FDR correction. In Moth, se-\n30\t                                                   mantic relevance showed consistent negative effects across all 30 ROIs, while surprisal showed\n31\t                                                   no comparable pattern. These findings suggest that semantic relevance is a promising BOLD-\n32\t                                                   sensitive metric of contextual semantic fit. More broadly, our findings support the view that\n33\t                                                   slow hemodynamic responses during naturalistic speech comprehension may be especially sensi-\n34\t                                                   tive to contextual semantic integration, whereas local probabilistic prediction error may be more\n35\t                                                   difficult to detect reliably with fMRI. In this sense, semantic relevance extends computational\n36\t                                                   models of language comprehension from prediction alone toward context-sensitive semantic in-\n37\t                                                   tegration.\n38\t\n39\t                                         Key Words: surprisal; semantic integration; hemodynamic response; FIR/deconvolution; neural\n40\t                                         timescale\n41\t\n42\t\n43\t                                         1        Introduction\n44\t                                         Understanding speech in natural contexts requires listeners to process a rapidly unfolding acoustic\n45\t                                         signal while building a coherent representation of events, entities, and relations over time. This\n46\t                                         process is incremental. Each incoming word is interpreted against prior context, but it can also\n47\t                                         update the listener’s current interpretation. Naturalistic language paradigms are therefore useful\n48\t                                         because they preserve the temporal continuity, contextual richness, and semantic diversity of ev-\n49\t                                         eryday comprehension (Hamilton and Huth, 2020; Huth et al., 2016). They also make it possible\n50\t                                             ∗\n51\t                                                 kunsun@tongji.edu.cn\n52\t                                             †\n53\t                                                 rong.wang@uni-tuebingen.de\n54\t\n55\t\n56\t\n57\t                                                                                                  1\n58\t\fto ask whether different computational dimensions of comprehension are expressed differently in\n59\tneural data.\n60\t    A central debate concerns the relation between prediction and integration. Information-theoretic\n61\taccounts propose that the processing cost of a word is related to its negative log probability given\n62\tthe preceding context, or surprisal (Hale, 2001; Levy, 2008). Prediction-based accounts further pro-\n63\tpose that comprehenders can use context to pre-activate likely upcoming linguistic input, although\n64\tthe strength, level, and necessity of prediction remain debated (Kuperberg and Jaeger, 2016; Pick-\n65\tering and Gambi, 2018). Electrophysiological (EEG) evidence has often linked predictability and\n66\tsurprisal to N400-family responses, consistent with rapid lexical-semantic access or expectation-\n67\trelated processing (Kutas and Hillyard, 1984; Kutas and Federmeier, 2011; DeLong et al., 2005;\n68\tFrank et al., 2015; Lau et al., 2008). Several fMRI studies have also reported surprisal-related BOLD\n69\teffects, particularly in temporal and inferior frontal regions (Willems et al., 2016; Brennan et al.,\n70\t2016; Henderson et al., 2016; Shain et al., 2020; Song et al., 2024), although these findings have not\n71\tbeen consistently replicated across stimuli, language models, and analysis approaches. Recent neu-\n72\troimaging and electrophysiological studies have identified hierarchical prediction-related responses\n73\tduring natural speech comprehension, although the detectability and spatial distribution of such\n74\teffects depend on the linguistic level, computational model, and neural measurement employed\n75\t(Caucheteux et al., 2023). Several studies have further shown that incorporating semantic informa-\n76\ttion into surprisal-based models can improve the modeling of BOLD responses during naturalistic\n77\tnarrative comprehension (Russo et al., 2020).\n78\t    However, naturalistic speech comprehension also requires semantic integration. Incoming words\n79\tare related to recently processed words, combined with semantic memory, and incorporated into\n80\tan evolving interpretation of the narrative. Neurobiological models of language emphasize that\n81\tcomprehension depends on multiple interacting operations, including memory retrieval, unifica-\n82\ttion or integration, prediction, and control (Hagoort, 2013; Lau et al., 2008). Retrieval-based\n83\taccounts further highlight the role of memory access mechanisms in sentence processing, whereby\n84\teach incoming word triggers cue-based retrieval from a decaying memory representation (Lewis\n85\tand Vasishth, 2005). In addition, semantic cognition is supported by distributed temporal, inferior\n86\tparietal, frontal, and medial systems rather than by a single classical language area (Binder and\n87\tDesai, 2011; Lambon Ralph et al., 2017; Seghier, 2013). Naturalistic fMRI studies are especially\n88\trelevant here because they show that semantic information during story comprehension is repre-\n89\tsented across broad cortical systems (Wehbe et al., 2014; Huth et al., 2016; Jain and Huth, 2018;\n90\tKauf et al., 2024; Sassenhagen and Fiebach, 2020). Recent evidence suggests that the brain may\n91\tcombine relatively short incoming contexts with incrementally accumulated long-term contextual\n92\trepresentations, rather than processing the entire preceding discourse in parallel (Tikochinski et al.,\n93\t2025), and embedding-based transformation could predict human neural activities (Goldstein et al.,\n94\t2022; Kumar et al., 2024).\n95\t    These theoretical debates are closely tied to measurement timescale. Surprisal may index a\n96\tfast local prediction-error-like signal, which is well suited to EEG and eye-movement measures.\n97\tBy contrast, fMRI measures a delayed and temporally smoothed BOLD response (Boynton et al.,\n98\t1996; Logothetis, 2003). In continuous speech, words arrive rapidly and adjacent hemodynamic\n99\tresponses overlap, potentially making brief word-level prediction-error effects difficult to isolate. At\n100\tthe same time, higher-order cortical regions integrate information over longer temporal windows\n101\tduring naturalistic comprehension (Hasson et al., 2008; Lerner et al., 2011; Hasson et al., 2015).\n102\tMore recent evidence further suggests that narrative information flows across a cortical hierarchy\n103\tcharacterized by progressively longer processing timescales, with temporally lagged interactions\n104\tbetween shorter- and longer-timescale regions (Chang et al., 2022). BOLD may therefore be more\n105\tsensitive to contextual semantic variables that unfold over several seconds than to brief word-level\n106\t\n107\t                                                   2\n108\t\ffluctuations in probabilistic unexpectedness.\n109\t     To understand the role of contextual semantic information, the current study examines a com-\n110\tputational metric that we define (contextual) semantic relevance. Operationally, semantic relevance\n111\tis computed as a distance-weighted combination of cosine similarities between a target word’s em-\n112\tbedding and those of its three preceding context words, supplemented by pairwise context-context\n113\tsimilarity (see Section 2.2 for the formal definition). Rather than asking how unexpected a word\n114\tis, semantic relevance asks how strongly an incoming word relates to, fits with, or contributes to\n115\tthe recent semantic context. A word can be locally unexpected but still semantically appropriate,\n116\tand a predictable word can contribute little additional semantic structure. This distinction moti-\n117\tvates the hypothesis that surprisal and semantic relevance are not simply alternative labels for the\n118\tsame process. Instead, they may index partially different computations and timescales: surprisal\n119\treflects local probabilistic expectation, whereas semantic relevance reflects contextual semantic fit\n120\tor integration.\n121\t     The present study examines this account using two public naturalistic speech comprehension\n122\tfMRI datasets with different statistical structures. The Alice dataset provides strong group align-\n123\tment because many participants listened to the same short literary narrative (Bhattasali et al.,\n124\t2020). The Moth dataset provides richer and more heterogeneous natural speech because fewer\n125\tparticipants listened to multiple autobiographical podcast stories (LeBel et al., 2023). The current\n126\tstudy addresses three research questions: (1) Does semantic relevance predict BOLD responses\n127\tafter controlling for lexical and timing variables, and does it show HRF-consistent delayed response\n128\tprofiles? (2) Is semantic relevance more robust than surprisal across datasets and modeling frame-\n129\tworks? (3) Do the two metrics show distinguishable patterns across ROI-level analyses, consistent\n130\twith partially different underlying computations?\n131\t\n132\t\n133\t2     Materials and Methods\n134\t2.1   Datasets\n135\tAlice fMRI dataset. The Alice dataset (abbreviated as Alice) contains fMRI data from par-\n136\tticipants listening to the first chapter of Alice’s Adventures in Wonderland (Bhattasali et al.,\n137\t2020). The fMRI sample includes 26 participants who listened passively to the same 12.4-minute\n138\taudiobook stimulus. The stimulus contains 2,129 words and was acquired with TR = 2 s, yield-\n139\ting 372 time points. This dataset provides a compact and highly aligned naturalistic design: all\n140\tparticipants heard the same literary narrative, the same word sequence, and the same discourse pro-\n141\tgression. This makes Alice especially useful for group-level ROI analyses and for estimating shared\n142\tdelayed response profiles with FIR/deconvolution. In the present study, the Alice dataset serves as\n143\tthe higher-participant, tightly aligned test case for whether semantic relevance is associated with\n144\tBOLD responses during naturalistic story comprehension.\n145\t\n146\tMoth fMRI dataset. The Moth dataset (abbreviated as Moth) contains fMRI responses recorded\n147\twhile 8 participants listened to 27 natural autobiographical stories from the Moth podcasts (LeBel\n148\tet al., 2023). Small N (= 8) still works for detecting within-dataset time-series associations, but it\n149\tlimits population-level generalization. Functional data were acquired with TR = 2 s. Compared\n150\twith the Alice dataset, the Moth stories are longer, more heterogeneous, and more naturalistic, with\n151\tvariation in speaker identity, speaking style, topic, prosody, and discourse structure. The Moth\n152\tdataset therefore provides a complementary test case, and it samples a broader semantic space and\n153\tcontains substantially more speech per participant, but it has fewer participants and weaker group-\n154\tlevel stimulus alignment. This design is valuable for testing whether semantic relevance effects\n155\t\n156\t                                                  3\n157\t\fgeneralize beyond a single literary narrative to more variable real-world speech, while also making\n158\tthe statistical detection of ROI-level effects more challenging.\n159\t\n160\tComplementary role of the two datasets. The two datasets allow a stronger test than either\n161\tdataset alone. Alice provides sensitivity for shared group-level effects because many participants\n162\theard the same short stimulus. Moth provides ecological breadth because the stimuli include many\n163\tnatural podcast narratives. If semantic relevance is associated with BOLD in both datasets, then\n164\tthe effect is unlikely to be specific to one story, one speaker, or one preprocessing pipeline. At\n165\tthe same time, differences between Alice and Moth are informative: a robust effect in Alice but a\n166\tmore constrained effect in Moth would suggest that semantic relevance is a plausible BOLD-related\n167\tmetric whose detectability depends on stimulus alignment, participant number, and story-level\n168\theterogeneity.\n169\t\n170\t2.2   Computational Metrics\n171\tWe compared two word-level computational metrics: word surprisal and semantic relevance. The\n172\tcentral theoretical contrast is that surprisal measures local probabilistic unexpectedness, whereas\n173\tsemantic relevance measures contextual semantic fit.\n174\t\n175\tSurprisal. Surprisal was treated as a metric of local probabilistic unexpectedness. For a target\n176\tword wt , surprisal is defined as:\n177\t\n178\t                                Surprisal(wt ) = − log P (wt | w<t ).                            (1)\n179\t    In the Alice dataset, we computed word-level surprisal using GPT-2 rather than relying on\n180\tthe available surprisal annotations. In the Moth dataset, surprisal was likewise derived primarily\n181\tfrom GPT-2, with GPT-Neo used as a robustness check. Surprisal was interpreted as a measure of\n182\tlocal probabilistic unexpectedness: higher values indicate words that are less expected given the\n183\tpreceding context.\n184\t\n185\tSemantic relevance. Semantic relevance quantifies how strongly a target word is semantically\n186\tconnected to its recent local context. Unlike surprisal, which estimates how unexpected a word\n187\tis, semantic relevance estimates the degree of semantic fit between the target word and the words\n188\tthat have been processed. The metric was motivated by the assumption that local contextual\n189\tinformation is not equally available during incremental comprehension. Recent words tend to have\n190\tstronger influence on current processing than more distant words (Cowan, 2001; Oberauer, 2002;\n191\tLewis and Vasishth, 2005; Christiansen and Chater, 2016). This local-context view is also consistent\n192\twith EEG and eye-tracking evidence that short-range semantic context predicts neural and reading-\n193\ttime responses during naturalistic comprehension (Frank and Willems, 2017; Broderick et al., 2018;\n194\tSun and Wang, 2026b; Sun et al., 2023; Sun and Wang, 2026a; Sun and Liu, 2024; Sun and Wang,\n195\t2022, 2026c; Sun et al., 2026).\n196\t     The general semantic relevance algorithm combines two sources of information: target-context\n197\tsemantic fit and context-context semantic coherence. For a target word wt , we represent the target\n198\tand its three preceding context words, wt−3 , wt−2 , and wt−1 , using embedding vectors. In static\n199\tembedding implementations, these vectors were derived from Model2vec word embeddings (Tulkens\n200\tand van Dongen, 2024). We first compute the cosine similarity between the target vector and each\n201\tcontext-word vector. These target-context similarities estimate how strongly the target word fits\n202\t\n203\t\n204\t\n205\t                                                 4\n206\t\fthe recent semantic context. To reflect graded contextual availability, the three preceding words\n207\treceive distance-based weights, with closer words receiving larger weights.\n208\t    The metric also includes pairwise semantic similarities among the three preceding context words.\n209\tThese context-context similarities capture the local semantic coherence of the material already\n210\tprocessed before the target word is encountered. In the present metric, target-context similarity\n211\twas treated as the direct semantic fit between the incoming word and the recent context, whereas\n212\tcontext-context similarity was treated as the background coherence already present in the preceding\n213\tcontext. Thus, semantic relevance combines two sources of information: the semantic fit between\n214\tthe target word and the recent context, and the semantic coherence within that context.\n215\t    Formally, semantic relevance for target word wt is:\n216\t                                    X                                    X\n217\t               SemRel(wt ) =                     αk · Sim(vt , vk ) +             β · Sim(vk , vl ),   (2)\n218\t                               k∈{t−3,t−2,t−1}                          (k,l)∈P\n219\t\n220\t    where vi denotes the embedding vector for word wi , P = {(t−3, t−2), (t−3, t−1), (t−2, t−1)},\n221\tand β is the fixed weight assigned to pairwise context-context similarity. The second term captures\n222\tthe local semantic coherence already present among the preceding context words. Cosine similarity\n223\tis defined as:\n224\t                                                          vi · v j\n225\t                                      Sim(vi , vj ) =               .                                  (3)\n226\t                                                         ∥vi ∥∥vj ∥\n227\t    The distance-based target-context weights were generated from a linear recency-decay func-\n228\ttion. Motivated by time-based working-memory decay models, we approximated recency-based\n229\tcontextual availability as a word-distance decay function (Oberauer and Lewandowsky, 2011; Gau-\n230\tvrit and Mathy, 2018). During online comprehension, recently encountered words are assumed to\n231\tremain more accessible in working memory and to exert stronger influence on the interpretation\n232\tof the target word, whereas more distant words become less available as memory traces decay or\n233\tare displaced by intervening material (Cowan, 2001; Oberauer, 2002; Lewis and Vasishth, 2005;\n234\tChristiansen and Chater, 2016). We therefore assigned larger weights to more recent context words\n235\tusing the following function:\n236\t\n237\t                                                   m−d+1\n238\t                                     αt−d = αmax ·          ,                                 (4)\n239\t                                                       m\n240\t    where d denotes the distance between the target word and the context word, m is the size of\n241\tthe local context window, and αmax is the maximum weight assigned to the immediately preceding\n242\tword. In the present study, we used a three-word context window (m = 3) and set αmax = 0.9,\n243\tyielding αt−1 = 0.9, αt−2 = 0.6, and αt−3 = 0.3. The context-context weight was fixed at β = 0.2,\n244\tlower than the target-context weights, because this term captures background semantic coherence\n245\tamong the preceding words rather than the direct fit of the target word itself. All weights and\n246\tthe window size were fixed before any fMRI modeling and should not be interpreted as parameters\n247\toptimized on brain data. Alternative weighting functions, such as exponential decay or equal\n248\tweighting, and alternative window sizes would be useful targets for future confirmatory analyses.\n249\tA higher semantic relevance value indicates stronger semantic fit between the target word and its\n250\trecent context, together with stronger semantic coherence within that context. The computation\n251\tof semantic relevance is illustrated in Figure 1.\n252\t\n253\tControl predictors. Models included lexical and timing controls where available. Alice models\n254\tincluded log (word frequency), word length, word duration, and random effects (Desai et al., 2020;\n255\t\n256\t\n257\t                                                     5\n258\t\fFigure 1: Schematic illustration of the semantic relevance metric in a reduced semantic-vector\n259\tspace. The example is “... went applebee slice sizzling apple pie put candle”, with “pie” as the\n260\ttarget word. The gray line shows the word sequence path. The three immediately preceding words,\n261\t“slice”, “sizzling”, and “apple”, form the local context. Purple links indicate target-context seman-\n262\ttic fit, computed as cosine similarity between the target-word vector and each context-word vector,\n263\tweighted by recency weights αk . Cyan dashed links indicate the context-coherence component,\n264\tcomputed from pairwise similarities among the local context words and weighted by β. The orange\n265\tarrow schematically indicates that the word-level semantic relevance predictor is later mapped to\n266\tBOLD responses through hemodynamic modeling. The figure is intended as a conceptual visual-\n267\tization of the metric and is not a statistical activation map.\n268\t\n269\t\n270\tSchuster et al., 2016; Gillis et al., 2023). Moth GAMMs included log (word frequency), word\n271\tlength, and random effects; the Moth FIR/deconvolution models additionally included run random\n272\teffects. FIR/deconvolution analyses also included lagged control predictors and slow time effects.\n273\tWe note that several potentially relevant nuisance variables, including acoustic envelope, speech\n274\trate, phonological complexity, word position in sentence, and semantic diversity, were not included\n275\t\n276\t\n277\t                                                 6\n278\t\fin the current models. The absence of these controls is a limitation, and future analyses should\n279\tincorporate them to more precisely isolate the contribution of semantic relevance (see Section 4.6).\n280\t\n281\t2.3   FIR/deconvolution Analysis of Original BOLD\n282\tTo test delayed hemodynamic response profiles, we modeled original continuous BOLD time series\n283\tusing FIR/deconvolution. FIR/deconvolution preserves the continuous time series and estimates\n284\tseparate effects at multiple post-word-onset delays. This makes it possible to ask whether a pre-\n285\tdictor has the delayed temporal profile expected of a hemodynamic response.\n286\t    For each predictor, lagged regressors were constructed across post-word-onset delays. Alice\n287\tFIR models tested semantic relevance and surprisal while controlling for FIR-lagged log (word fre-\n288\tquency), word length, duration, slow time, and subject effects. Grouped FIR tests assessed whether\n289\teach predictor explained BOLD variance across the full lag profile. This standard FIR/deconvolution\n290\tapproach was appropriate for Alice because all participants listened to the same short narrative,\n291\tproviding strong temporal alignment across subjects.\n292\t    For the Moth dataset, ordinary grouped FIR tests were less sensitive to semantic relevance\n293\teffects. We therefore used an HRF-weighted 4–12 s directional contrast as an exploratory, Alice-\n294\tinformed follow-up analysis, rather than as a fully independent confirmatory test. This contrast\n295\tweighted FIR lags corresponding to 4, 6, 8, 10, and 12 s (i.e., lags 2–6 at TR = 2 s) and tested\n296\twhether semantic relevance showed a consistent negative delayed effect. The time window was\n297\tmotivated by the expected timing of the canonical BOLD response and by the delayed semantic\n298\trelevance profile observed in Alice. Because the analysis window was selected after observing the\n299\tAlice results, the Moth directional test should be interpreted as a constrained exploratory analysis,\n300\tand its results require validation with a preregistered metric and independent held-out data. The\n301\tMoth FIR model included the semantic relevance HRF-weighted contrast, a surprisal HRF-weighted\n302\tcontrast, FIR-lagged log frequency and word length controls, slow time, subject random effects,\n303\tand run random effects.\n304\t\n305\t2.4   Transformed BOLD and HRF-convolved Predictors\n306\tWe used transformed BOLD data for further statistical analyses. Transformed BOLD refers to\n307\tderived ROI-level response tables in which the BOLD signal has been aligned with word-level or\n308\tTR-level predictors and expressed as an analyzable response variable for each ROI, participant, and\n309\tstimulus time point. Since such tables can depend on alignment, interpolation, HRF shifting, and\n310\tthe mapping between words and TRs, they are not used as the primary basis for timing-sensitive\n311\tinference.\n312\t    The Alice dataset included precomputed word-level transformed BOLD tables from the original\n313\tdataset release (Bhattasali et al., 2020), in which ROI-level responses were already aligned to the\n314\tword sequence. The Moth dataset did not provide equivalent word-aligned ROI tables, so we\n315\tconstructed HRF-convolved predictor time series by convolving word-level metrics with a canonical\n316\tHRF and sampling them at the fMRI TR resolution (LeBel et al., 2023).\n317\t    Specifically, for Alice, transformed BOLD tables were available at the word/ROI level and\n318\tincluded the linguistic metrics, control predictors, subject labels, and transformed BOLD response\n319\tvalues. As word duration was available in Alice, duration was included as a covariate. For Moth,\n320\tword-level metrics were first converted into BOLD-like predictor time series. Each word-level metric\n321\twas convolved with a canonical HRF and then sampled or aligned at the fMRI TR resolution.\n322\tThis procedure produces HRF-convolved predictor series that approximate the delayed BOLD\n323\tresponse expected from each linguistic variable. Duration was omitted from the Moth GAMMs\n324\t\n325\t\n326\t                                                 7\n327\t\fwhen unavailable. The HRF-weighted 4–12 s window was selected based on the delayed semantic-\n328\trelevance profile observed in the Alice FIR/deconvolution analysis and on the expected timing of\n329\tthe canonical hemodynamic response. Therefore, the Moth FIR/deconvolution analysis was treated\n330\tas an Alice-informed exploratory convergence analysis rather than a fully independent confirmatory\n331\treplication.\n332\t    As an additional stability check, we performed a split-half analysis within the Moth dataset by\n333\tdividing stories into two non-overlapping subsets and applying the same fixed 4–12 s HRF-weighted\n334\tdirectional test separately to each subset. In addition, as the GAMM inputs were constructed\n335\tdifferently across datasets, differences in GAMM partial-effect shapes between Alice and Moth\n336\tshould be interpreted cautiously and may reflect preprocessing and alignment choices as well as\n337\tdataset-specific neural responses.\n338\t    This transformed-BOLD strategy is complementary to FIR/deconvolution but has important\n339\tlimitations. Transformed BOLD models are useful for visualizing the shape of partial effects, espe-\n340\tcially nonlinear associations, but they do not by themselves recover the full hemodynamic response\n341\tprofile and may inflate apparent precision if multiple word-level observations inherit information\n342\tfrom the same TR-level BOLD sample. Therefore, we treat GAMMs on transformed BOLD as ex-\n343\tploratory effect-shape analyses, and FIR/deconvolution on original BOLD as the primary analysis\n344\tfor delayed hemodynamic timing.\n345\t\n346\t2.5   GAMM Analysis of Transformed BOLD\n347\tWe modeled transformed BOLD data using generalized additive mixed models (GAMMs). GAMMs\n348\tare useful because they allow continuous predictors to have potentially nonlinear effects while\n349\talso accounting for repeated observations from the same participants. However, because the\n350\ttransformed-BOLD analyses were not the primary basis for hemodynamic timing inference, these\n351\tmodels were interpreted as supplementary analyses of effect presence and shape.\n352\t    For the Alice dataset, a separate model was fitted for each ROI:We modeled transformed BOLD\n353\tdata using generalized additive mixed models (GAMMs). GAMMs are useful because they allow\n354\tsmooth nonlinear effects of continuous predictors while also including random-effect terms for par-\n355\tticipants. However, because the transformed-BOLD tables are not the primary unit for hemody-\n356\tnamic timing inference, these GAMMs were interpreted as supplementary effect-shape models. For\n357\tAlice, each ROI was fit using:\n358\t\n359\t\n360\t               bold ∼ s(log freq, k = 5) + s(wordlen, k = 5) + s(duration, k = 5)\n361\t                                                                                                (5)\n362\t                      + s(surprisal, k = 5) + s(SemRel, k = 5) + s(subj, bs = “re”).\n363\t\n364\t   For Moth, duration was omitted when unavailable, and HRF-convolved predictor time series\n365\twere used:\n366\t\n367\t\n368\t                     bold ∼ s(log freqHRF , k = 5) + s(wordlenHRF , k = 5)\n369\t                            + s(surprisalHRF , k = 5) + s(SemRelHRF , k = 5)                    (6)\n370\t                            + s(subj, bs = “re”).\n371\t\n372\t    Here, SemRel denotes semantic relevance. The notation s(x) represents a smooth function of\n373\tpredictor x, allowing its association with BOLD amplitude to be nonlinear rather than imposing a\n374\tstrictly linear relationship. The parameter k specifies the basis dimension, which sets the maximum\n375\tcomplexity available to the smooth. We used k = 5 to permit moderately flexible effect shapes\n376\t\n377\t                                                8\n378\t\fwhile limiting overfitting; the effective complexity of each smooth was determined during model\n379\tfitting through penalization. The term s(subj, bs = “re”) specifies a participant-level random effect.\n380\tIt allows each participant to have a different baseline BOLD level, thereby accounting for repeated\n381\tobservations and between-participant variability.\n382\t     Accordingly, s(SemRel) estimates the partial association between semantic relevance and trans-\n383\tformed BOLD while holding the other predictors constant, whereas s(surprisal) estimates the corre-\n384\tsponding partial association for surprisal. These models were used to determine whether semantic\n385\trelevance and surprisal were associated with BOLD amplitude and to visualize the shapes of these\n386\tassociations across ROIs.\n387\t\n388\tComplementary role of GAMM and FIR/deconvolution. The two statistical approaches\n389\tanswer related but different questions. GAMMs on transformed BOLD ask whether a predictor is\n390\tassociated with BOLD amplitude and what the partial-effect curve looks like after controlling for\n391\tother variables. FIR/deconvolution asks when the effect appears in the original BOLD time series\n392\tand whether it follows a plausible delayed HRF profile. Thus, GAMM provides an interpretable but\n393\tsupplementary effect-shape analysis, whereas FIR/deconvolution provides timing-sensitive evidence\n394\tabout delayed BOLD responses. Because the transformed-BOLD and FIR analyses can differ in\n395\tscaling, centering, and temporal alignment, apparent agreement or disagreement between their\n396\teffect directions should be interpreted cautiously.\n397\t\n398\t2.6   Multiple Comparisons\n399\tFor ROI-level tests, p-values were corrected using Benjamini–Hochberg false discovery rate (FDR)\n400\tcorrection within explicitly defined test families. Alice grouped FIR tests were corrected separately\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24218416-49cb-4659-887b-8543d119258d","uuid":"9a47fbb1-4b49-4049-aef2-1497a7898290","timestamp":"2026-07-20T07:47:13.729Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_review/paper.txt","content":"                                             Contextual Semantic Relevance Tracks fMRI BOLD Responses\n                                                      During Naturalistic Speech Comprehension\n                                                                                  Kun Sun1 and Rong Wang2\n\n                                                                     Department of Linguistics, Tongji University ∗\n                                                                      1\n                                                           2\n                                                             Department of Computational Linguistics, Tuebingen University †\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                              Abstract\n                                                       Naturalistic language comprehension requires listeners to process both local probabilistic\narXiv:2607.15856v1 [cs.CL] 17 Jul 2026\n\n\n\n\n                                                   expectations and contextual semantic relations. Surprisal has been widely used to quantify lo-\n                                                   cal word unexpectedness, but evidence that it robustly predicts fMRI BOLD responses during\n                                                   continuous comprehension has been mixed. This study investigates whether contextual seman-\n                                                   tic relevance, defined as how strongly an incoming word relates to its recent semantic context,\n                                                   predicts BOLD responses during naturalistic speech comprehension. We analyzed two pub-\n                                                   lic fMRI datasets, the Alice dataset and the Moth dataset, treating them as complementary\n                                                   rather than identical replications. Transformed BOLD responses were modeled with generalized\n                                                   additive mixed models (GAMMs) and original continuous BOLD time series were tested with\n                                                   FIR/deconvolution analyses. In Alice, semantic relevance was significant across all 12 ROIs\n                                                   (region of interest), whereas surprisal was not significant after FDR correction. In Moth, se-\n                                                   mantic relevance showed consistent negative effects across all 30 ROIs, while surprisal showed\n                                                   no comparable pattern. These findings suggest that semantic relevance is a promising BOLD-\n                                                   sensitive metric of contextual semantic fit. More broadly, our findings support the view that\n                                                   slow hemodynamic responses during naturalistic speech comprehension may be especially sensi-\n                                                   tive to contextual semantic integration, whereas local probabilistic prediction error may be more\n                                                   difficult to detect reliably with fMRI. In this sense, semantic relevance extends computational\n                                                   models of language comprehension from prediction alone toward context-sensitive semantic in-\n                                                   tegration.\n\n                                         Key Words: surprisal; semantic integration; hemodynamic response; FIR/deconvolution; neural\n                                         timescale\n\n\n                                         1        Introduction\n                                         Understanding speech in natural contexts requires listeners to process a rapidly unfolding acoustic\n                                         signal while building a coherent representation of events, entities, and relations over time. This\n                                         process is incremental. Each incoming word is interpreted against prior context, but it can also\n                                         update the listener’s current interpretation. Naturalistic language paradigms are therefore useful\n                                         because they preserve the temporal continuity, contextual richness, and semantic diversity of ev-\n                                         eryday comprehension (Hamilton and Huth, 2020; Huth et al., 2016). They also make it possible\n                                             ∗\n                                                 kunsun@tongji.edu.cn\n                                             †\n                                                 rong.wang@uni-tuebingen.de\n\n\n\n                                                                                                  1\n\fto ask whether different computational dimensions of comprehension are expressed differently in\nneural data.\n    A central debate concerns the relation between prediction and integration. Information-theoretic\naccounts propose that the processing cost of a word is related to its negative log probability given\nthe preceding context, or surprisal (Hale, 2001; Levy, 2008). Prediction-based accounts further pro-\npose that comprehenders can use context to pre-activate likely upcoming linguistic input, although\nthe strength, level, and necessity of prediction remain debated (Kuperberg and Jaeger, 2016; Pick-\nering and Gambi, 2018). Electrophysiological (EEG) evidence has often linked predictability and\nsurprisal to N400-family responses, consistent with rapid lexical-semantic access or expectation-\nrelated processing (Kutas and Hillyard, 1984; Kutas and Federmeier, 2011; DeLong et al., 2005;\nFrank et al., 2015; Lau et al., 2008). Several fMRI studies have also reported surprisal-related BOLD\neffects, particularly in temporal and inferior frontal regions (Willems et al., 2016; Brennan et al.,\n2016; Henderson et al., 2016; Shain et al., 2020; Song et al., 2024), although these findings have not\nbeen consistently replicated across stimuli, language models, and analysis approaches. Recent neu-\nroimaging and electrophysiological studies have identified hierarchical prediction-related responses\nduring natural speech comprehension, although the detectability and spatial distribution of such\neffects depend on the linguistic level, computational model, and neural measurement employed\n(Caucheteux et al., 2023). Several studies have further shown that incorporating semantic informa-\ntion into surprisal-based models can improve the modeling of BOLD responses during naturalistic\nnarrative comprehension (Russo et al., 2020).\n    However, naturalistic speech comprehension also requires semantic integration. Incoming words\nare related to recently processed words, combined with semantic memory, and incorporated into\nan evolving interpretation of the narrative. Neurobiological models of language emphasize that\ncomprehension depends on multiple interacting operations, including memory retrieval, unifica-\ntion or integration, prediction, and control (Hagoort, 2013; Lau et al., 2008). Retrieval-based\naccounts further highlight the role of memory access mechanisms in sentence processing, whereby\neach incoming word triggers cue-based retrieval from a decaying memory representation (Lewis\nand Vasishth, 2005). In addition, semantic cognition is supported by distributed temporal, inferior\nparietal, frontal, and medial systems rather than by a single classical language area (Binder and\nDesai, 2011; Lambon Ralph et al., 2017; Seghier, 2013). Naturalistic fMRI studies are especially\nrelevant here because they show that semantic information during story comprehension is repre-\nsented across broad cortical systems (Wehbe et al., 2014; Huth et al., 2016; Jain and Huth, 2018;\nKauf et al., 2024; Sassenhagen and Fiebach, 2020). Recent evidence suggests that the brain may\ncombine relatively short incoming contexts with incrementally accumulated long-term contextual\nrepresentations, rather than processing the entire preceding discourse in parallel (Tikochinski et al.,\n2025), and embedding-based transformation could predict human neural activities (Goldstein et al.,\n2022; Kumar et al., 2024).\n    These theoretical debates are closely tied to measurement timescale. Surprisal may index a\nfast local prediction-error-like signal, which is well suited to EEG and eye-movement measures.\nBy contrast, fMRI measures a delayed and temporally smoothed BOLD response (Boynton et al.,\n1996; Logothetis, 2003). In continuous speech, words arrive rapidly and adjacent hemodynamic\nresponses overlap, potentially making brief word-level prediction-error effects difficult to isolate. At\nthe same time, higher-order cortical regions integrate information over longer temporal windows\nduring naturalistic comprehension (Hasson et al., 2008; Lerner et al., 2011; Hasson et al., 2015).\nMore recent evidence further suggests that narrative information flows across a cortical hierarchy\ncharacterized by progressively longer processing timescales, with temporally lagged interactions\nbetween shorter- and longer-timescale regions (Chang et al., 2022). BOLD may therefore be more\nsensitive to contextual semantic variables that unfold over several seconds than to brief word-level\n\n                                                   2\n\ffluctuations in probabilistic unexpectedness.\n     To understand the role of contextual semantic information, the current study examines a com-\nputational metric that we define (contextual) semantic relevance. Operationally, semantic relevance\nis computed as a distance-weighted combination of cosine similarities between a target word’s em-\nbedding and those of its three preceding context words, supplemented by pairwise context-context\nsimilarity (see Section 2.2 for the formal definition). Rather than asking how unexpected a word\nis, semantic relevance asks how strongly an incoming word relates to, fits with, or contributes to\nthe recent semantic context. A word can be locally unexpected but still semantically appropriate,\nand a predictable word can contribute little additional semantic structure. This distinction moti-\nvates the hypothesis that surprisal and semantic relevance are not simply alternative labels for the\nsame process. Instead, they may index partially different computations and timescales: surprisal\nreflects local probabilistic expectation, whereas semantic relevance reflects contextual semantic fit\nor integration.\n     The present study examines this account using two public naturalistic speech comprehension\nfMRI datasets with different statistical structures. The Alice dataset provides strong group align-\nment because many participants listened to the same short literary narrative (Bhattasali et al.,\n2020). The Moth dataset provides richer and more heterogeneous natural speech because fewer\nparticipants listened to multiple autobiographical podcast stories (LeBel et al., 2023). The current\nstudy addresses three research questions: (1) Does semantic relevance predict BOLD responses\nafter controlling for lexical and timing variables, and does it show HRF-consistent delayed response\nprofiles? (2) Is semantic relevance more robust than surprisal across datasets and modeling frame-\nworks? (3) Do the two metrics show distinguishable patterns across ROI-level analyses, consistent\nwith partially different underlying computations?\n\n\n2     Materials and Methods\n2.1   Datasets\nAlice fMRI dataset. The Alice dataset (abbreviated as Alice) contains fMRI data from par-\nticipants listening to the first chapter of Alice’s Adventures in Wonderland (Bhattasali et al.,\n2020). The fMRI sample includes 26 participants who listened passively to the same 12.4-minute\naudiobook stimulus. The stimulus contains 2,129 words and was acquired with TR = 2 s, yield-\ning 372 time points. This dataset provides a compact and highly aligned naturalistic design: all\nparticipants heard the same literary narrative, the same word sequence, and the same discourse pro-\ngression. This makes Alice especially useful for group-level ROI analyses and for estimating shared\ndelayed response profiles with FIR/deconvolution. In the present study, the Alice dataset serves as\nthe higher-participant, tightly aligned test case for whether semantic relevance is associated with\nBOLD responses during naturalistic story comprehension.\n\nMoth fMRI dataset. The Moth dataset (abbreviated as Moth) contains fMRI responses recorded\nwhile 8 participants listened to 27 natural autobiographical stories from the Moth podcasts (LeBel\net al., 2023). Small N (= 8) still works for detecting within-dataset time-series associations, but it\nlimits population-level generalization. Functional data were acquired with TR = 2 s. Compared\nwith the Alice dataset, the Moth stories are longer, more heterogeneous, and more naturalistic, with\nvariation in speaker identity, speaking style, topic, prosody, and discourse structure. The Moth\ndataset therefore provides a complementary test case, and it samples a broader semantic space and\ncontains substantially more speech per participant, but it has fewer participants and weaker group-\nlevel stimulus alignment. This design is valuable for testing whether semantic relevance effects\n\n                                                  3\n\fgeneralize beyond a single literary narrative to more variable real-world speech, while also making\nthe statistical detection of ROI-level effects more challenging.\n\nComplementary role of the two datasets. The two datasets allow a stronger test than either\ndataset alone. Alice provides sensitivity for shared group-level effects because many participants\nheard the same short stimulus. Moth provides ecological breadth because the stimuli include many\nnatural podcast narratives. If semantic relevance is associated with BOLD in both datasets, then\nthe effect is unlikely to be specific to one story, one speaker, or one preprocessing pipeline. At\nthe same time, differences between Alice and Moth are informative: a robust effect in Alice but a\nmore constrained effect in Moth would suggest that semantic relevance is a plausible BOLD-related\nmetric whose detectability depends on stimulus alignment, participant number, and story-level\nheterogeneity.\n\n2.2   Computational Metrics\nWe compared two word-level computational metrics: word surprisal and semantic relevance. The\ncentral theoretical contrast is that surprisal measures local probabilistic unexpectedness, whereas\nsemantic relevance measures contextual semantic fit.\n\nSurprisal. Surprisal was treated as a metric of local probabilistic unexpectedness. For a target\nword wt , surprisal is defined as:\n\n                                Surprisal(wt ) = − log P (wt | w<t ).                            (1)\n    In the Alice dataset, we computed word-level surprisal using GPT-2 rather than relying on\nthe available surprisal annotations. In the Moth dataset, surprisal was likewise derived primarily\nfrom GPT-2, with GPT-Neo used as a robustness check. Surprisal was interpreted as a measure of\nlocal probabilistic unexpectedness: higher values indicate words that are less expected given the\npreceding context.\n\nSemantic relevance. Semantic relevance quantifies how strongly a target word is semantically\nconnected to its recent local context. Unlike surprisal, which estimates how unexpected a word\nis, semantic relevance estimates the degree of semantic fit between the target word and the words\nthat have been processed. The metric was motivated by the assumption that local contextual\ninformation is not equally available during incremental comprehension. Recent words tend to have\nstronger influence on current processing than more distant words (Cowan, 2001; Oberauer, 2002;\nLewis and Vasishth, 2005; Christiansen and Chater, 2016). This local-context view is also consistent\nwith EEG and eye-tracking evidence that short-range semantic context predicts neural and reading-\ntime responses during naturalistic comprehension (Frank and Willems, 2017; Broderick et al., 2018;\nSun and Wang, 2026b; Sun et al., 2023; Sun and Wang, 2026a; Sun and Liu, 2024; Sun and Wang,\n2022, 2026c; Sun et al., 2026).\n     The general semantic relevance algorithm combines two sources of information: target-context\nsemantic fit and context-context semantic coherence. For a target word wt , we represent the target\nand its three preceding context words, wt−3 , wt−2 , and wt−1 , using embedding vectors. In static\nembedding implementations, these vectors were derived from Model2vec word embeddings (Tulkens\nand van Dongen, 2024). We first compute the cosine similarity between the target vector and each\ncontext-word vector. These target-context similarities estimate how strongly the target word fits\n\n\n\n                                                 4\n\fthe recent semantic context. To reflect graded contextual availability, the three preceding words\nreceive distance-based weights, with closer words receiving larger weights.\n    The metric also includes pairwise semantic similarities among the three preceding context words.\nThese context-context similarities capture the local semantic coherence of the material already\nprocessed before the target word is encountered. In the present metric, target-context similarity\nwas treated as the direct semantic fit between the incoming word and the recent context, whereas\ncontext-context similarity was treated as the background coherence already present in the preceding\ncontext. Thus, semantic relevance combines two sources of information: the semantic fit between\nthe target word and the recent context, and the semantic coherence within that context.\n    Formally, semantic relevance for target word wt is:\n                                    X                                    X\n               SemRel(wt ) =                     αk · Sim(vt , vk ) +             β · Sim(vk , vl ),   (2)\n                               k∈{t−3,t−2,t−1}                          (k,l)∈P\n\n    where vi denotes the embedding vector for word wi , P = {(t−3, t−2), (t−3, t−1), (t−2, t−1)},\nand β is the fixed weight assigned to pairwise context-context similarity. The second term captures\nthe local semantic coherence already present among the preceding context words. Cosine similarity\nis defined as:\n                                                          vi · v j\n                                      Sim(vi , vj ) =               .                                  (3)\n                                                         ∥vi ∥∥vj ∥\n    The distance-based target-context weights were generated from a linear recency-decay func-\ntion. Motivated by time-based working-memory decay models, we approximated recency-based\ncontextual availability as a word-distance decay function (Oberauer and Lewandowsky, 2011; Gau-\nvrit and Mathy, 2018). During online comprehension, recently encountered words are assumed to\nremain more accessible in working memory and to exert stronger influence on the interpretation\nof the target word, whereas more distant words become less available as memory traces decay or\nare displaced by intervening material (Cowan, 2001; Oberauer, 2002; Lewis and Vasishth, 2005;\nChristiansen and Chater, 2016). We therefore assigned larger weights to more recent context words\nusing the following function:\n\n                                                   m−d+1\n                                     αt−d = αmax ·          ,                                 (4)\n                                                       m\n    where d denotes the distance between the target word and the context word, m is the size of\nthe local context window, and αmax is the maximum weight assigned to the immediately preceding\nword. In the present study, we used a three-word context window (m = 3) and set αmax = 0.9,\nyielding αt−1 = 0.9, αt−2 = 0.6, and αt−3 = 0.3. The context-context weight was fixed at β = 0.2,\nlower than the target-context weights, because this term captures background semantic coherence\namong the preceding words rather than the direct fit of the target word itself. All weights and\nthe window size were fixed before any fMRI modeling and should not be interpreted as parameters\noptimized on brain data. Alternative weighting functions, such as exponential decay or equal\nweighting, and alternative window sizes would be useful targets for future confirmatory analyses.\nA higher semantic relevance value indicates stronger semantic fit between the target word and its\nrecent context, together with stronger semantic coherence within that context. The computation\nof semantic relevance is illustrated in Figure 1.\n\nControl predictors. Models included lexical and timing controls where available. Alice models\nincluded log (word frequency), word length, word duration, and random effects (Desai et al., 2020;\n\n\n                                                     5\n\fFigure 1: Schematic illustration of the semantic relevance metric in a reduced semantic-vector\nspace. The example is “... went applebee slice sizzling apple pie put candle”, with “pie” as the\ntarget word. The gray line shows the word sequence path. The three immediately preceding words,\n“slice”, “sizzling”, and “apple”, form the local context. Purple links indicate target-context seman-\ntic fit, computed as cosine similarity between the target-word vector and each context-word vector,\nweighted by recency weights αk . Cyan dashed links indicate the context-coherence component,\ncomputed from pairwise similarities among the local context words and weighted by β. The orange\narrow schematically indicates that the word-level semantic relevance predictor is later mapped to\nBOLD responses through hemodynamic modeling. The figure is intended as a conceptual visual-\nization of the metric and is not a statistical activation map.\n\n\nSchuster et al., 2016; Gillis et al., 2023). Moth GAMMs included log (word frequency), word\nlength, and random effects; the Moth FIR/deconvolution models additionally included run random\neffects. FIR/deconvolution analyses also included lagged control predictors and slow time effects.\nWe note that several potentially relevant nuisance variables, including acoustic envelope, speech\nrate, phonological complexity, word position in sentence, and semantic diversity, were not included\n\n\n                                                 6\n\fin the current models. The absence of these controls is a limitation, and future analyses should\nincorporate them to more precisely isolate the contribution of semantic relevance (see Section 4.6).\n\n2.3   FIR/deconvolution Analysis of Original BOLD\nTo test delayed hemodynamic response profiles, we modeled original continuous BOLD time series\nusing FIR/deconvolution. FIR/deconvolution preserves the continuous time series and estimates\nseparate effects at multiple post-word-onset delays. This makes it possible to ask whether a pre-\ndictor has the delayed temporal profile expected of a hemodynamic response.\n    For each predictor, lagged regressors were constructed across post-word-onset delays. Alice\nFIR models tested semantic relevance and surprisal while controlling for FIR-lagged log (word fre-\nquency), word length, duration, slow time, and subject effects. Grouped FIR tests assessed whether\neach predictor explained BOLD variance across the full lag profile. This standard FIR/deconvolution\napproach was appropriate for Alice because all participants listened to the same short narrative,\nproviding strong temporal alignment across subjects.\n    For the Moth dataset, ordinary grouped FIR tests were less sensitive to semantic relevance\neffects. We therefore used an HRF-weighted 4–12 s directional contrast as an exploratory, Alice-\ninformed follow-up analysis, rather than as a fully independent confirmatory test. This contrast\nweighted FIR lags corresponding to 4, 6, 8, 10, and 12 s (i.e., lags 2–6 at TR = 2 s) and tested\nwhether semantic relevance showed a consistent negative delayed effect. The time window was\nmotivated by the expected timing of the canonical BOLD response and by the delayed semantic\nrelevance profile observed in Alice. Because the analysis window was selected after observing the\nAlice results, the Moth directional test should be interpreted as a constrained exploratory analysis,\nand its results require validation with a preregistered metric and independent held-out data. The\nMoth FIR model included the semantic relevance HRF-weighted contrast, a surprisal HRF-weighted\ncontrast, FIR-lagged log frequency and word length controls, slow time, subject random effects,\nand run random effects.\n\n2.4   Transformed BOLD and HRF-convolved Predictors\nWe used transformed BOLD data for further statistical analyses. Transformed BOLD refers to\nderived ROI-level response tables in which the BOLD signal has been aligned with word-level or\nTR-level predictors and expressed as an analyzable response variable for each ROI, participant, and\nstimulus time point. Since such tables can depend on alignment, interpolation, HRF shifting, and\nthe mapping between words and TRs, they are not used as the primary basis for timing-sensitive\ninference.\n    The Alice dataset included precomputed word-level transformed BOLD tables from the original\ndataset release (Bhattasali et al., 2020), in which ROI-level responses were already aligned to the\nword sequence. The Moth dataset did not provide equivalent word-aligned ROI tables, so we\nconstructed HRF-convolved predictor time series by convolving word-level metrics with a canonical\nHRF and sampling them at the fMRI TR resolution (LeBel et al., 2023).\n    Specifically, for Alice, transformed BOLD tables were available at the word/ROI level and\nincluded the linguistic metrics, control predictors, subject labels, and transformed BOLD response\nvalues. As word duration was available in Alice, duration was included as a covariate. For Moth,\nword-level metrics were first converted into BOLD-like predictor time series. Each word-level metric\nwas convolved with a canonical HRF and then sampled or aligned at the fMRI TR resolution.\nThis procedure produces HRF-convolved predictor series that approximate the delayed BOLD\nresponse expected from each linguistic variable. Duration was omitted from the Moth GAMMs\n\n\n                                                 7\n\fwhen unavailable. The HRF-weighted 4–12 s window was selected based on the delayed semantic-\nrelevance profile observed in the Alice FIR/deconvolution analysis and on the expected timing of\nthe canonical hemodynamic response. Therefore, the Moth FIR/deconvolution analysis was treated\nas an Alice-informed exploratory convergence analysis rather than a fully independent confirmatory\nreplication.\n    As an additional stability check, we performed a split-half analysis within the Moth dataset by\ndividing stories into two non-overlapping subsets and applying the same fixed 4–12 s HRF-weighted\ndirectional test separately to each subset. In addition, as the GAMM inputs were constructed\ndifferently across datasets, differences in GAMM partial-effect shapes between Alice and Moth\nshould be interpreted cautiously and may reflect preprocessing and alignment choices as well as\ndataset-specific neural responses.\n    This transformed-BOLD strategy is complementary to FIR/deconvolution but has important\nlimitations. Transformed BOLD models are useful for visualizing the shape of partial effects, espe-\ncially nonlinear associations, but they do not by themselves recover the full hemodynamic response\nprofile and may inflate apparent precision if multiple word-level observations inherit information\nfrom the same TR-level BOLD sample. Therefore, we treat GAMMs on transformed BOLD as ex-\nploratory effect-shape analyses, and FIR/deconvolution on original BOLD as the primary analysis\nfor delayed hemodynamic timing.\n\n2.5   GAMM Analysis of Transformed BOLD\nWe modeled transformed BOLD data using generalized additive mixed models (GAMMs). GAMMs\nare useful because they allow continuous predictors to have potentially nonlinear effects while\nalso accounting for repeated observations from the same participants. However, because the\ntransformed-BOLD analyses were not the primary basis for hemodynamic timing inference, these\nmodels were interpreted as supplementary analyses of effect presence and shape.\n    For the Alice dataset, a separate model was fitted for each ROI:We modeled transformed BOLD\ndata using generalized additive mixed models (GAMMs). GAMMs are useful because they allow\nsmooth nonlinear effects of continuous predictors while also including random-effect terms for par-\nticipants. However, because the transformed-BOLD tables are not the primary unit for hemody-\nnamic timing inference, these GAMMs were interpreted as supplementary effect-shape models. For\nAlice, each ROI was fit using:\n\n\n               bold ∼ s(log freq, k = 5) + s(wordlen, k = 5) + s(duration, k = 5)\n                                                                                                (5)\n                      + s(surprisal, k = 5) + s(SemRel, k = 5) + s(subj, bs = “re”).\n\n   For Moth, duration was omitted when unavailable, and HRF-convolved predictor time series\nwere used:\n\n\n                     bold ∼ s(log freqHRF , k = 5) + s(wordlenHRF , k = 5)\n                            + s(surprisalHRF , k = 5) + s(SemRelHRF , k = 5)                    (6)\n                            + s(subj, bs = “re”).\n\n    Here, SemRel denotes semantic relevance. The notation s(x) represents a smooth function of\npredictor x, allowing its association with BOLD amplitude to be nonlinear rather than imposing a\nstrictly linear relationship. The parameter k specifies the basis dimension, which sets the maximum\ncomplexity available to the smooth. We used k = 5 to permit moderately flexible effect shapes\n\n                                                8\n\fwhile limiting overfitting; the effective complexity of each smooth was determined during model\nfitting through penalization. The term s(subj, bs = “re”) specifies a participant-level random effect.\nIt allows each participant to have a different baseline BOLD level, thereby accounting for repeated\nobservations and between-participant variability.\n     Accordingly, s(SemRel) estimates the partial association between semantic relevance and trans-\nformed BOLD while holding the other predictors constant, whereas s(surprisal) estimates the corre-\nsponding partial association for surprisal. These models were used to determine whether semantic\nrelevance and surprisal were associated with BOLD amplitude and to visualize the shapes of these\nassociations across ROIs.\n\nComplementary role of GAMM and FIR/deconvolution. The two statistical approaches\nanswer related but different questions. GAMMs on transformed BOLD ask whether a predictor is\nassociated with BOLD amplitude and what the partial-effect curve looks like after controlling for\nother variables. FIR/deconvolution asks when the effect appears in the original BOLD time series\nand whether it follows a plausible delayed HRF profile. Thus, GAMM provides an interpretable but\nsupplementary effect-shape analysis, whereas FIR/deconvolution provides timing-sensitive evidence\nabout delayed BOLD responses. Because the transformed-BOLD and FIR analyses can differ in\nscaling, centering, and temporal alignment, apparent agreement or disagreement between their\neffect directions should be interpreted cautiously.\n\n2.6   Multiple Comparisons\nFor ROI-level tests, p-values were corrected using Benjamini–Hochberg false discovery rate (FDR)\ncorrection within explicitly defined test families. Alice grouped FIR tests were corrected separately","numLines":400,"startLine":1,"totalLines":1645}}}
