{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-a04d36a7740abd22","type":"tool_result","content":"400\tcorrection within explicitly defined test families. Alice grouped FIR tests were corrected separately\n401\tfor semantic relevance across the 12 ROIs and for surprisal across the 12 ROIs. Alice GAMM\n402\tsmooth terms were corrected separately within each smooth predictor across the 12 ROIs. Moth\n403\tHRF-weighted FIR tests were corrected separately within each candidate semantic relevance metric\n404\tacross the 30 analyzable ROIs; directional negative tests and two-sided LRT tests were reported as\n405\tseparate exploratory families. Moth GAMM smooth terms were corrected across the 30 analyzable\n406\tROIs for the plotted predictor. We report the number of ROIs surviving FDR correction at q < .05.\n407\t\n408\t\n409\t3     Results\n410\t3.1   Analysis overview\n411\tSpeech comprehension relies on interacting temporal and frontal systems, including ventral and\n412\tdorsal processing pathways, rather than on a single classical language region (Specht, 2014). To\n413\tmaximize cross-dataset comparability, the primary analyses focused on the 12 ROIs available in\n414\tboth datasets: AG, CG, FOC, HG, IC, IFG, MTG, PT, SG, SMG, STG, and vmPFC. These\n415\tcommon ROIs provided the basis for evaluating whether semantic relevance and surprisal showed\n416\tconceptually convergent effects across the Alice and Moth datasets.\n417\t    Because the Moth dataset contained substantially more naturalistic speech and provided ana-\n418\tlyzable transformed-BOLD and original-BOLD FIR/deconvolution time series for a broader set of\n419\tregions, we additionally conducted an exploratory extended analysis across 30 ROIs. In addition\n420\tto the 12 common ROIs, the extended Moth analysis included ACC, AI, COC, DLPFC, FUS,\n421\tHPC, ITG, LING, LOC, OFG, PCG, PCUN, PHG, PP, preSMA, RSC, SFG, and TP. Accordingly,\n422\tcross-dataset comparisons are based primarily on the 12 common ROIs, whereas the expanded\n423\t30-ROI Moth analysis is used to examine whether the observed effects extend to broader auditory,\n424\t\n425\t\n426\t                                                  9\n427\t\flanguage, memory, control, and narrative-processing systems. The 30-ROI set was smaller than\n428\tthe full collection of anatomical masks available for the Moth dataset because several masks did\n429\tnot have corresponding combined ROI-level BOLD tables in the current analysis pipeline.\n430\t    Collectively, these ROIs support the distributed neural processes involved in naturalistic story\n431\tlistening. Temporal and auditory regions, including HG, STG, MTG, PT, and ITG, contribute to\n432\tacoustic, phonological, lexical, and semantic processing. Frontal, opercular, and insular regions, in-\n433\tcluding IFG, FOC, DLPFC, SFG, preSMA, IC, and AI, support speech-related processing, working\n434\tmemory, cognitive control, salience detection, and semantic selection. Parietal regions, including\n435\tAG, SMG, PP, and PCUN, contribute to attention, multimodal integration, and the construction of\n436\tcoherent situation models. Medial temporal and default-mode regions, including HPC, PHG, RSC,\n437\tvmPFC, and TP, support memory, contextual association, emotional evaluation, and narrative-level\n438\tintegration. In short, these regions form a broad network involved in speech perception, language\n439\tcomprehension, memory, cognitive control, and the integration of information across an unfolding\n440\tnarrative. The commonly associated functions of the individual ROIs are summarized in Table 1\n441\tin Appendix A.\n442\t    Moreover, Pearson correlation analyses showed that semantic relevance and surprisal were only\n443\tweakly related in both datasets. In Alice, semantic relevance was weakly negatively correlated\n444\twith surprisal (r = -0.18), and in Moth the correlation was near zero (r = -0.01). This indicates\n445\tthat semantic relevance and surprisal capture largely distinct word-level properties rather than two\n446\tversions of the same metric. Thus, the stronger BOLD association for semantic relevance cannot\n447\tbe explained simply by high collinearity with surprisal. The correlation heatmap (Figure 7) is\n448\tpresented in Appendix A.\n449\t\n450\t3.2     Results of the Alice Dataset\n451\t3.2.1    Semantic relevance for FIR/deconvolution effects\n452\tIn the Alice original-BOLD FIR/deconvolution analysis, the available semantic similarity metric\n453\twas significant in all 12 ROIs after FDR correction. In contrast, surprisal was not significant in\n454\tany ROI after FDR correction. The corrected semantic relevance effects were strong across the\n455\tROI set, with the smallest within-predictor FDR values observed in STG and MTG. The lag-level\n456\tcoefficients showed that semantic relevance effects were concentrated at delayed lags, consistent\n457\twith a hemodynamic response profile rather than an instantaneous word-level artifact. As shown\n458\tin Figure 2, Panel (a) provides the anatomical summary of significant ROIs, panel (b) ranks ROIs\n459\tby corrected significance, and panel (c) shows the temporal FIR lag profile that reveals when the\n460\tsemantic relevance effect emerges after word onset. the three panels show that semantic relevance\n461\twas significantly associated with delayed BOLD responses across Alice ROIs, with effects con-\n462\tcentrated in the expected hemodynamic-response window. Thus, in Alice, the dataset-provided\n463\tsemantic relevance metric was robust in both transformed-BOLD GAMMs and original-BOLD\n464\tFIR/deconvolution, whereas surprisal was not robust in the original-BOLD timing analysis.\n465\t\n466\t3.2.2    Transformed-BOLD GAMMs Results\n467\tIn the Alice transformed-BOLD GAMMs, the dataset-provided semantic similarity metric was a\n468\tsignificant smooth term in all 12 ROIs. The smooth term for semsim was significant in AG, CG,\n469\tFOC, HG, IC, IFG, MTG, PT, SG, SMG, STG, and vmPFC. Surprisal showed significant smooth\n470\teffects in 6 of the 12 ROIs (FOC, HG, IFG, MTG, PT, and STG), indicating that transformed\n471\tBOLD can contain local surprisal-related structure. Because transformed-BOLD observations may\n472\tnot be independent at the word level, these GAMM findings are used primarily to describe effect\n473\t\n474\t                                                 10\n475\t\fa    Significant semantic relevance regions                                                                                                    b\n476\t     Surface color shows ROI-level FIR/deconvolution significance.\n477\t                                                                                                                                      ROI-ranked significance\n478\t                                                                                                                                                FDR q=.05\n479\t                                                                                                                              STG                                                                  t=-3.15\n480\t                                                                                                                             MTG                                                         t=-2.92             8\n481\t                                                                                                                               IFG                                             t=-2.53\n482\t                                                                                                                                AG                                             t=-2.48                       6\n483\t\n484\t\n485\t\n486\t\n487\t                                                                                                                                  