{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-b116f86a176c5cdd","type":"tool_result","content":"900\t                                                  19\n901\t\flation may therefore explain why surprisal is significant in some datasets or brain regions but not\n902\tconsistently across studies.\n903\t    The present results therefore support a complementary-computation interpretation. They do\n904\tnot show that prediction is unimportant, nor do they imply that semantic relevance replaces sur-\n905\tprisal. Rather, they suggest that contextual semantic fit may be more robustly visible in slow BOLD\n906\tresponses than local probabilistic error. This provides a possible bridge between psycholinguistic\n907\ttheories of prediction and neurobiological accounts of semantic integration.\n908\t\n909\t4.4   Fast EEG responses and slow hemodynamic timescales\n910\tAnother implication concerns the temporal scales at which lexical expectation and contextual se-\n911\tmantic fit become detectable. Surprisal and predictability effects are well established in temporally\n912\tprecise measures such as EEG and eye movements. In EEG, predictable or semantically fitting\n913\twords typically elicit reduced N400 amplitudes, linking contextual expectation and semantic ac-\n914\tcess to neural responses within a few hundred milliseconds after word onset (Kutas and Hillyard,\n915\t1984; Kutas and Federmeier, 2011; Lau et al., 2008; Frank et al., 2015). Eye-movement studies\n916\tsimilarly show that word predictability and contextual constraint influence fixation durations and\n917\tother reading behaviors during incremental comprehension (Rayner et al., 1996; Smith and Levy,\n918\t2013; Sun et al., 2026).\n919\t    A companion naturalistic-reading EEG analysis provides converging evidence (Sun and Wang,\n920\t2026b). Across 22 participants and 32 channels, both semantic relevance and surprisal were asso-\n921\tciated with N400 and P600 responses, but with partly distinguishable temporal profiles. Semantic\n922\trelevance showed broader effects in the N400 window, whereas surprisal exhibited comparatively\n923\tstronger modulation around the P600 interval. The weak correlation between the two metrics in\n924\tthat dataset further suggests that they capture partly distinct aspects of word-level processing.\n925\t    These EEG results indicate that semantic relevance should not be understood exclusively as\n926\ta slow process. Recent ECoG evidence similarly shows that earlier and deeper language-model\n927\trepresentations correspond to earlier and later stages of cortical language processing, respectively\n928\t(Goldstein et al., 2025). Computational measures differing in contextual depth may therefore be\n929\tmost detectable at different neural timescales. Contextual semantic fit can influence neural activity\n930\twithin several hundred milliseconds, affecting both early semantic access or integration and later\n931\tupdating or reanalysis. At the same time, EEG preserves rapid word-locked fluctuations that may\n932\tbe attenuated in fMRI. BOLD responses are delayed and temporally smoothed (Boynton et al.,\n933\t1996; Logothetis, 2003), and in continuous speech the hemodynamic responses elicited by adjacent\n934\twords overlap substantially. A brief and rapidly varying surprisal-related response may therefore\n935\tbe difficult to isolate in BOLD, particularly after controlling for correlated lexical variables such as\n936\tfrequency, word length, and duration.\n937\t    Semantic relevance may be comparatively well aligned with the temporal characteristics of\n938\tBOLD because it is computed from overlapping relations between each target word and its recent\n939\tcontext. Although each estimate is word-specific, adjacent estimates share contextual information\n940\tand may track semantic structure that evolves continuously over several words. Such temporally\n941\textended contextual variation may survive hemodynamic smoothing more readily than highly local\n942\tfluctuations in probabilistic unexpectedness. This interpretation is compatible with evidence for\n943\thierarchical temporal receptive windows across cortex, whereby early auditory and language regions\n944\trespond to relatively short-timescale information, whereas higher-order temporal, parietal, and\n945\tdefault-mode regions integrate information over longer periods during naturalistic comprehension\n946\t(Hasson et al., 2008; Lerner et al., 2011; Hasson et al., 2015). Chang et al. (2022) further showed\n947\tthat information during narrative comprehension propagates across this cortical timescale hierarchy,\n948\t\n949\t\n950\t                                                  20\n951\t\fproviding a systems-level framework for understanding why context-sensitive semantic variables\n952\tmay be expressed as delayed and spatially distributed BOLD responses.\n953\t    In sum, the EEG and fMRI findings suggest a difference in measurement sensitivity rather than\n954\ta strict separation between fast and slow linguistic computations. Both surprisal and semantic\n955\trelevance can modulate rapid EEG responses, but semantic relevance may also generate temporally\n956\tsustained variation that is more readily detectable in the slow BOLD signal. Surprisal-related\n957\tBOLD effects may therefore be more dependent on stimulus structure, language-model specification,\n958\ttemporal alignment, and the control variables included in the analysis.\n959\t\n960\t4.5   Naturalistic semantic networks and situation-model updating\n961\tThe use of naturalistic spoken narratives is central to the present study. Real story comprehension\n962\trequires listeners to maintain and update characters, events, goals, causal relations, and discourse\n963\tcontext over time. Naturalistic fMRI studies have shown that semantic information is represented\n964\tacross distributed cortical systems rather than being confined to classical language areas (Huth\n965\tet al., 2016; Wehbe et al., 2014; Jain and Huth, 2018). This broader organization makes naturalistic\n966\tdatasets especially useful for testing predictors related to contextual semantic fit.\n967\t    Semantic relevance may therefore relate to a distributed comprehension network. The present\n968\tROI-level results are broadly consistent with this view but also reveal an informative gradient. In\n969\tthe Moth dataset, the strongest semantic relevance effects were observed in CG, ACC, vmPFC,\n970\tand PCUN (these regions associated with cognitive control, contextual integration, and situation-\n971\tmodel construction ) rather than in classical perisylvian language areas such as STG, MTG, or IFG,\n972\twhich showed weaker (though still significant) effects. This pattern is consistent with the idea that\n973\tsemantic relevance primarily indexes discourse-level contextual fit and situation-model updating\n974\t(Ferstl et al., 2008), rather than lower-level lexical-semantic access. In Alice, by contrast, the\n975\tstrongest FIR effects were in STG and MTG, possibly reflecting the stronger temporal alignment\n976\tand stimulus control in that dataset. These regional differences across datasets underscore the\n977\tneed for future voxel-wise analyses that can more precisely localize the neural sources of semantic\n978\trelevance effects (Binder and Desai, 2011; Lambon Ralph et al., 2017; Seghier, 2013).\n979\t    At the same time, widespread effects should be interpreted cautiously. Broad ROI-level sig-\n980\tnificance, especially in the Moth dataset, does not imply that all regions encode semantic rele-\n981\tvance in the same way. Some effects may reflect core semantic processing, whereas others may\n982\treflect attention, memory, narrative structure, global temporal dynamics, or unmodeled acoustic\n983\tand discourse-level covariates. The safe conclusion is that semantic relevance tracks a naturalistic\n984\tcomprehension signal that plausibly relates to contextual semantic integration and situation-model\n985\tupdating, but future work should use nuisance controls, temporal surrogate analyses, and held-\n986\tout encoding models to determine which components of this distributed response are specifically\n987\tsemantic.\n988\t\n989\t4.6   Methodological implications\n990\tThe results have broader implications for computational neuroscience of language. Computational\n991\tpredictors should not be treated as interchangeable regressors simply because they are derived from\n992\tthe same words. Surprisal and semantic relevance make different claims about neural computation.\n993\tSurprisal indexes local probabilistic unexpectedness, whereas semantic relevance indexes contextual\n994\tsemantic fit and integration. These computations may operate over partly different timescales and\n995\tmay therefore require different statistical models.\n996\t    Recent work has demonstrated that GPT-based encoding models can predict sentence-level\n997\t\n998\t\n999\t                                                 21\n1000\t\fresponses in the human language network and can identify novel sentences that reliably drive or\n1001\tsuppress its activity, with surprisal and linguistic well-formedness emerging as important determi-\n1002\tnants of response strength (Tuckute et al., 2024). These findings illustrate the power of computa-\n1003\ttional representations for predicting and manipulating neural responses to language. Nevertheless,\n1004\tsuccessful brain prediction by a computational representation does not by itself establish that the\n1005\tbrain implements the model’s training objective or computational mechanism (Antonello and Huth,\n1006\t2024). Accordingly, the stronger association between semantic relevance and BOLD in the present\n1007\tanalyses should be interpreted as evidence for the neural sensitivity of the metric, rather than as\n1008\tproof that the brain explicitly computes semantic relevance in the precise form implemented here.\n1009\t    The complementary use of GAMMs and FIR/deconvolution is important for this reason. GAMMs\n1010\tapplied to transformed or HRF-convolved BOLD are useful for testing nonlinear predictor-response\n1011\trelationships while controlling lexical and subject-level variability. FIR/deconvolution applied to\n1012\toriginal continuous BOLD is useful for estimating the delayed response profile without forcing a\n1013\tsingle canonical HRF shape. In short, these methods allow one to ask both whether a predictor\n1014\texplains BOLD variance and when its effect emerges after word onset. This issue is especially\n1015\timportant because BOLD is a low-pass signal and semantic relevance is itself temporally smoother\n1016\tthan surprisal.\n1017\t    Recent work has introduced methods for estimating semantic relevance and shown that these\n1018\tmetrics predict eye movements during reading across multiple languages (Sun and Liu, 2024; Sun\n1019\tet al., 2026). Related studies further suggest that semantic relevance may contribute to modeling\n1020\tspeech production, spontaneous speech characteristics, EEG responses, and visual attention (Sun\n1021\tand Wang, 2026c,b,a). The present study extends this line of research by demonstrating that\n1022\tsemantic relevance also predicts BOLD responses during language comprehension.\n1023\t    In spite of these, several limitations should be considered. As semantic relevance is temporally\n1024\tsmoother than surprisal, some effects may reflect better alignment with BOLD’s low-frequency\n1025\tstructure rather than semantic processing alone. In addition, unmodeled factors such as acoustic\n1026\tproperties, speech rate, story progression, motion, scanner drift, global signal, and temporal au-\n1027\ttocorrelation may contribute to the observed effects. The Moth dataset also included only eight\n1028\tparticipants, limiting group-level generalizability despite its rich within-participant data. Finally,\n1029\tthe fMRI findings are related to companion EEG evidence only at the interpretive level rather than\n1030\tthrough a joint cross-modal analysis.\n1031\t\n1032\t\n1033\t5    Conclusion\n1034\tAcross two naturalistic fMRI datasets, semantic relevance was associated with BOLD responses\n1035\tduring spoken-language comprehension, whereas surprisal showed weaker and less consistent effects\n1036\tin these ROI-level analyses. These findings suggest that contextual semantic fit may be more readily\n1037\texpressed in slow hemodynamic responses than local word-level unexpectedness. The contribution\n1038\tof semantic relevance to computational neuroscience is that it provides a computable bridge between\n1039\tword-level language models and slower neural dynamics measured with fMRI. Unlike surprisal,\n1040\twhich captures forward prediction error, semantic relevance quantifies how an incoming word fits\n1041\tinto the recent semantic context, making it useful for modeling sustained integration processes that\n1042\tunfold across discourse and engage distributed cortical systems.\n1043\t    This distinction links different computational descriptions of language to different neural mea-\n1044\tsurement timescales. Surprisal may primarily capture fast prediction-related processing, whereas\n1045\tsemantic relevance may capture more sustained contextual integration that is better matched to the\n1046\ttemporal dynamics of BOLD. More broadly, the results argue that models of naturalistic language\n1047\t\n1048\t\n1049\t                                                 22\n1050\t\fcomprehension should move beyond forward prediction alone and explicitly incorporate contextual\n1051\tcoherence, semantic fit, and discourse-level integration as core components of neural language pro-\n1052\tcessing. Semantic relevance may therefore provide a useful bridge between computational models\n1053\tof lexical processing and neural systems supporting semantic integration, narrative comprehension,\n1054\tand situation-model updating.\n1055\t\n1056\t\n1057\tData and Code Availability\n1058\tAll analyses were conducted using publicly available fMRI datasets. The Alice data were obtained\n1059\tfrom the Alice dataset release, and the Moth data were obtained from the natural language fMRI\n1060\tdataset for voxelwise encoding models. Analysis scripts, intermediate result tables, and generated\n1061\tfigures are currently stored in the local project directory. The public repository is available at: .\n1062\t\n1063\t\n1064\tAcknowledgments\n1065\tWe thank the creators of the Alice and Moth datasets for making their naturalistic fMRI resources\n1066\tpublicly available.\n1067\t\n1068\t\n1069\tReferences\n1070\tRichard Antonello and Alexander Huth. Predictive coding or just feature discovery? an alternative\n1071\t  account of why language models fit brain data. Neurobiology of Language, 5(1):64–79, 2024.\n1072\tShohini Bhattasali, Jonathan R. Brennan, Wen-Ming Luh, Berta Franzluebbers, and John T. Hale.\n1073\t  The alice datasets: fmri & eeg observations of natural language comprehension. In Proceedings\n1074\t  of the 12th Conference on Language Resources and Evaluation (LREC 2020), pages 120–125.\n1075\t  European Language Resources Association, 2020.\n1076\tJeffrey R. Binder and Rutvik H. Desai. The neurobiology of semantic memory. Trends in Cognitive\n1077\t  Sciences, 15(11):527–536, 2011.\n1078\tGeoffrey M. Boynton, Stephen A. Engel, Gary H. Glover, and David J. Heeger. Linear systems\n1079\t analysis of functional magnetic resonance imaging in human v1. Journal of Neuroscience, 16(13):\n1080\t 4207–4221, 1996. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.16-13-04207.1996.\n1081\tJonathan R Brennan, Edward P Stabler, Sarah E Van Wagenen, Wen-Ming Luh, and John T Hale.\n1082\t  Abstract linguistic structure correlates with temporal activity during naturalistic comprehension.\n1083\t  In Brain and Language, volume 157–158, pages 81–94, 2016.\n1084\tMichael P. Broderick, Andrew J. Anderson, Giovanni M. Di Liberto, Michael J. Crosse, and Ed-\n1085\t mund C. Lalor. Electrophysiological correlates of semantic dissimilarity reflect the comprehension\n1086\t of natural, narrative speech. Current Biology, 28(5):803–809.e3, 2018. doi: 10.1016/j.cub.2018.\n1087\t 01.080.\n1088\tCharlotte Caucheteux, Alexandre Gramfort, and Jean-Rémi King. Evidence of a predictive coding\n1089\t hierarchy in the human brain listening to speech. Nature Human Behaviour, 7(3):430–441, 2023.\n1090\tClaire H. C. Chang, Samuel A. Nastase, and Uri Hasson. Information flow across the cortical\n1091\t  timescale hierarchy during narrative construction. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sci-\n1092\t  ences, 119(51):e2209307119, 2022.\n1093\t\n1094\t                                                 23\n1095\t\fMorten H. Christiansen and Nick Chater. The now-or-never bottleneck: A fundamental constraint\n1096\t on language. Behavioral and Brain Sciences, 39:e62, 2016. doi: 10.1017/S0140525X1500031X.\n1097\t\n1098\tNelson Cowan. The magical number 4 in short-term memory: A reconsideration of mental storage\n1099\t  capacity. Behavioral and Brain Sciences, 24(1):87–114, 2001. doi: 10.1017/S0140525X01003922.\n1100\t\n1101\tKatherine A. DeLong, Thomas P. Urbach, and Marta Kutas. Probabilistic word pre-activation\n1102\t during language comprehension inferred from electrical brain activity. Nature Neuroscience, 8:\n1103\t 1117–1121, 2005. doi: 10.1038/nn1504.\n1104\t\n1105\tFatma Deniz, Anwar O. Nunez-Elizalde, Alexander G. Huth, and Jack L. Gallant. The represen-\n1106\t  tation of semantic information across human cerebral cortex during listening versus reading is\n1107\t  invariant to stimulus modality. Journal of Neuroscience, 39(39):7722–7736, 2019.\n1108\t\n1109\tRutvik H. Desai, Wonil Choi, and John M. Henderson. Word frequency effects in naturalistic\n1110\t reading. Language, Cognition and Neuroscience, 35(5):583–594, 2020.\n1111\t\n1112\tEvelyn C Ferstl, Jane Neumann, Carsten Bogler, and D Yves von Cramon. The role of the medial\n1113\t  frontal cortex in text comprehension. NeuroImage, 40(4):1661–1673, 2008.\n1114\t\n1115\tStefan L. Frank and Roel M. Willems. Word predictability and semantic similarity show distinct\n1116\t  patterns of brain activity during language comprehension. Language, Cognition and Neuro-\n1117\t  science, 32(9):1192–1203, 2017. doi: 10.1080/23273798.2017.1323109.\n1118\t\n1119\tStefan L. Frank, Leun J. Otten, Giulia Galli, and Gabriella Vigliocco. The erp response to the\n1120\t  amount of information conveyed by words in sentences. Brain and Language, 140:1–11, 2015.\n1121\t  doi: 10.1016/j.bandl.2014.10.006.\n1122\t\n1123\tNicolas Gauvrit and Fabien Mathy. Mathematical transcription of the time-based resource sharing\n1124\t  theory of working memory. British Journal of Mathematical and Statistical Psychology, 71(1):\n1125\t  146–166, 2018.\n1126\t\n1127\tMarlies Gillis, Jonas Vanthornhout, and Tom Francart. Heard or understood? neural tracking of\n1128\t language features in a comprehensible story, an incomprehensible story and a word list. eNeuro,\n1129\t 10(7):ENEURO.0075–23.2023, 2023.\n1130\t\n1131\tAriel Goldstein, Zaid Zada, Eliav Buchnik, Mariano Schain, Amy Price, Bobbi Aubrey, Samuel A.\n1132\t  Nastase, Amir Feder, Dotan Emanuel, Alon Cohen, Aren Jansen, Harshvardhan Gazula, Gina\n1133\t  Choe, Aditi Rao, Catherine Kim, Colton Casto, Lora Fanda, Werner Doyle, Daniel Friedman,\n1134\t  Patricia Dugan, Lucia Melloni, Roi Reichart, Sasha Devore, Adeen Flinker, Uri Hasson, et al.\n1135\t  Shared computational principles for language processing in humans and deep language models.\n1136\t  Nature Neuroscience, 25(3):369–380, 2022.\n1137\t\n1138\tAriel Goldstein, Eric Ham, Mariano Schain, Samuel A. Nastase, Bobbi Aubrey, Zaid Zada, et al.\n1139\t  Temporal structure of natural language processing in the human brain corresponds to layered\n1140\t  hierarchy of large language models. Nature Communications, 16(1):10529, 2025.\n1141\t\n1142\tKalanit Grill-Spector, Richard Henson, and Alex Martin. Repetition and the brain: Neural models\n1143\t of stimulus-specific effects. Trends in Cognitive Sciences, 10(1):14–23, 2006.\n1144\t\n1145\tPeter Hagoort. Muc (memory, unification, control) and beyond. Frontiers in Psychology, 4:416,\n1146\t  2013.\n1147\t\n1148\t\n1149\t                                              24\n1150\t\fJohn Hale. A probabilistic earley parser as a psycholinguistic model. In Proceedings of the Second\n1151\t  Meeting of the North American Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics on\n1152\t  Language Technologies, pages 1–8. Association for Computational Linguistics, 2001. doi: 10.\n1153\t  3115/1073336.1073357.\n1154\t\n1155\tLiberty S. Hamilton and Alexander G. Huth. The revolution will not be controlled: Natural\n1156\t  stimuli in speech neuroscience. Language, Cognition and Neuroscience, 35(5):573–582, 2020. doi:\n1157\t  10.1080/23273798.2018.1499946.\n1158\t\n1159\tUri Hasson, Eunice Yang, Ignacio Vallines, David J. Heeger, and Nava Rubin. A hierarchy of\n1160\t  temporal receptive windows in human cortex. Journal of Neuroscience, 28(10):2539–2550, 2008.\n1161\t\n1162\tUri Hasson, Janice Chen, and Christopher J. Honey. Hierarchical process memory: Memory as\n1163\t  an integral component of information processing. Trends in Cognitive Sciences, 19(6):304–313,\n1164\t  2015.\n1165\t\n1166\tJohn M Henderson, Wonil Choi, Matthew W Lowder, and Fernanda Ferreira. Language structure\n1167\t  in the brain: A fixation-related fmri study of syntactic surprisal in reading. NeuroImage, 132:\n1168\t  293–300, 2016.\n1169\t\n1170\tAlexander G. Huth, Wendy A. de Heer, Thomas L. Griffiths, Frédéric E. Theunissen, and Jack L.\n1171\t  Gallant. Natural speech reveals the semantic maps that tile human cerebral cortex. Nature, 532:\n1172\t  453–458, 2016. doi: 10.1038/nature17637.\n1173\t\n1174\tShailee Jain and Alexander G. Huth. Incorporating context into language encoding models for\n1175\t  fmri. In Advances in Neural Information Processing Systems, volume 31, 2018.\n1176\t\n1177\tCarina Kauf, Greta Tuckute, Roger Levy, Jacob Andreas, and Evelina Fedorenko. Lexical-semantic\n1178\t  content, not syntactic structure, is the main contributor to ann-brain similarity of fmri responses\n1179\t  in the language network. Neurobiology of Language, 5(1):7–42, 2024.\n1180\t\n1181\tSreejan Kumar, Theodore R. Sumers, Takateru Yamakoshi, Ariel Goldstein, Uri Hasson, Ken-\n1182\t  neth A. Norman, Thomas L. Griffiths, Robert D. Hawkins, and Samuel A. Nastase. Shared\n1183\t  functional specialization in transformer-based language models and the human brain. Nature\n1184\t  Communications, 15(1):5523, 2024.\n1185\t\n1186\tGina R. Kuperberg and T. Florian Jaeger. What do we mean by prediction in language compre-\n1187\t  hension? Language, Cognition and Neuroscience, 31(1):32–59, 2016.\n1188\t\n1189\tMarta Kutas and Kara D. Federmeier. Thirty years and counting: Finding meaning in the n400\n1190\t component of the event-related brain potential (erp). Annual Review of Psychology, 62:621–647,\n1191\t 2011. doi: 10.1146/annurev.psych.093008.131123.\n1192\t\n1193\tMarta Kutas and Steven A. Hillyard. Brain potentials during reading reflect word expectancy and\n1194\t semantic association. Nature, 307:161–163, 1984. doi: 10.1038/307161a0.\n1195\t\n1196\tMatthew A. Lambon Ralph, Elizabeth Jefferies, Karalyn Patterson, and Timothy T. Rogers. The\n1197\t neural and computational bases of semantic cognition. Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 18(1):\n1198\t 42–55, 2017.\n1199\t\n1200\tEllen F. Lau, Colin Phillips, and David Poeppel. A cortical network for semantics: (de)constructing\n1201\t  the n400. Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 9(12):920–933, 2008.\n1202\t\n1203\t\n1204\t                                                 25\n1205\t\fAmanda LeBel, Lauren Wagner, Shailee Jain, Aneesh Adhikari-Desai, Bhavin Gupta, Allyson\n1206\t Morgenthal, Jerry Tang, Lixiang Xu, and Alexander G. Huth. A natural language fmri dataset\n1207\t for voxelwise encoding models. Scientific Data, 10:555, 2023. doi: 10.1038/s41597-023-02437-z.\n1208\t\n1209\tYulia Lerner, Christopher J. Honey, Lauren J. Silbert, and Uri Hasson. Topographic mapping of a\n1210\t  hierarchy of temporal receptive windows using a narrated story. Journal of Neuroscience, 31(8):\n1211\t  2906–2915, 2011.\n1212\t\n1213\tRoger Levy. Expectation-based syntactic comprehension. Cognition, 106(3):1126–1177, 2008. doi:\n1214\t  10.1016/j.cognition.2007.05.006.\n1215\t\n1216\tRichard L. Lewis and Shravan Vasishth. An activation-based model of sentence processing as skilled\n1217\t  memory retrieval. Cognitive Science, 29(3):375–419, 2005. doi: 10.1207/s15516709cog0000 25.\n1218\t\n1219\tNikos K. Logothetis. The underpinnings of the bold functional magnetic resonance imaging signal.\n1220\t  Journal of Neuroscience, 23(10):3963–3971, 2003. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.23-10-03963.2003.\n1221\t\n1222\tKlaus Oberauer. Access to information in working memory: Exploring the focus of attention.\n1223\t  Journal of Experimental Psychology: Learning, Memory, and Cognition, 28(3):411–421, 2002.\n1224\t  doi: 10.1037/0278-7393.28.3.411.\n1225\t\n1226\tKlaus Oberauer and Stephan Lewandowsky. Modeling working memory: A computational imple-\n1227\t  mentation of the time-based resource-sharing theory. Psychonomic Bulletin & Review, 18(1):\n1228\t  10–45, 2011. doi: 10.3758/s13423-010-0020-6.\n1229\t\n1230\tMartin J. Pickering and Chiara Gambi. Predicting while comprehending language: A theory and\n1231\t review. Psychological Bulletin, 144(10):1002–1044, 2018.\n1232\t\n1233\tKeith Rayner, Sara C Sereno, and Gary E Raney. Eye movement control in reading: A comparison of\n1234\t two types of models. Journal of Experimental Psychology: Human Perception and Performance,\n1235\t 22(5):1188–1200, 1996.\n1236\t\n1237\tAndrea G. Russo, Maria De Martino, Azzurra Mancuso, Giorgio Iaconetta, Renzo Manara, Anni-\n1238\t bale Elia, Alessandro Laudanna, Francesco Di Salle, and Fabrizio Esposito. Semantics-weighted\n1239\t lexical surprisal modeling of naturalistic functional mri time-series during spoken narrative lis-\n1240\t tening. NeuroImage, 222:117281, 2020.\n1241\t\n1242\tJona Sassenhagen and Christian J. Fiebach. Traces of meaning itself: Encoding distributional word\n1243\t  vectors in brain activity. Neurobiology of Language, 1(1):54–76, 2020.\n1244\t\n1245\tSarah Schuster, Stefan Hawelka, Florian Hutzler, Martin Kronbichler, and Fabio Richlan. Words\n1246\t  in context: The effects of length, frequency, and predictability on brain responses during natural\n1247\t  reading. Cerebral Cortex, 26(10):3889–3904, 2016.\n1248\t\n1249\tMohamed L. Seghier. The angular gyrus: multiple functions and multiple subdivisions. The\n1250\t Neuroscientist, 19(1):43–61, 2013.\n1251\t\n1252\tCory Shain, Idan Asher Blank, Marten van Schijndel, William Schuler, and Evelina Fedorenko.\n1253\t  fMRI reveals language-specific predictive coding during naturalistic sentence comprehension.\n1254\t  Neuropsychologia, 138:107307, 2020.\n1255\t\n1256\tNathaniel J Smith and Roger Levy. The effect of word predictability on reading time is logarithmic.\n1257\t Cognition, 128(3):302–319, 2013.\n1258\t\n1259\t                                                26\n1260\t\fMing Song, Jing Wang, and Qing Cai. The unique contribution of uncertainty reduction during\n1261\t naturalistic language comprehension. Cortex, 181:12–25, 2024.\n1262\t\n1263\tKarsten Specht. Neuronal basis of speech comprehension. Hearing Research, 307:121–135, 2014.\n1264\t\n1265\tKun Sun and Haitao Liu. Attention-aware semantic relevance predicting chinese sentence reading.\n1266\t Cognition, 2024.\n1267\t\n1268\tKun Sun and Rong Wang. Semantic similarity and mutual information predicting sentence com-\n1269\t prehension: the case of dangling topic construction in chinese. Journal of Cognitive Psychology,\n1270\t pages 1–24, 2022.\n1271\t\n1272\tKun Sun and Rong Wang. Contextual semantic relevance predicting human visual attention. IEEE\n1273\t Transactions on Cognitive and Developmental Systems, 2026a. doi: 10.1109/TCDS.2026.3683873.\n1274\t\n1275\tKun Sun and Rong Wang. Semantic integration and lexical expectation shape n400 and p600\n1276\t dynamics during naturalistic reading. arXiv, 2026b. arXiv:2607.04107.\n1277\t\n1278\tKun Sun and Rong Wang. Non-linear effects of semantic relevance on word duration in spontaneous\n1279\t speech. InterSpeech, 2026c.\n1280\t\n1281\tKun Sun, Qiuying Wang, and Xiaofei Lu. An interpretable measure of semantic similarity for\n1282\t predicting eye movements in reading. Psychonomic Bulletin & Review, pages 1–16, 2023.\n1283\t\n1284\tKun Sun, Rong Wang, and Harald Baayen. Semantic coherence predicts reading fixation durations\n1285\t across languages beyond surprisal and lexical factors. Linguistics, 2026.\n1286\t\n1287\tRefael Tikochinski, Ariel Goldstein, Yoav Meiri, Uri Hasson, and Roi Reichart. Incremental accumu-\n1288\t  lation of linguistic context in artificial and biological neural networks. Nature Communications,\n1289\t  16(1):803, 2025.\n1290\t\n1291\tGreta Tuckute, Aalok Sathe, Shashank Srikant, Maya Taliaferro, Mingye Wang, Martin Schrimpf,\n1292\t  Kendrick Kay, and Evelina Fedorenko. Driving and suppressing the human language network\n1293\t  using large language models. Nature Human Behaviour, 8(3):544–561, 2024.\n1294\t\n1295\tStephan Tulkens and Thomas van Dongen. Model2vec: Fast state-of-the-art static embeddings,\n1296\t  2024. URL https://github.com/MinishLab/model2vec.\n1297\t\n1298\tLeila Wehbe, Brian Murphy, Partha Talukdar, Alona Fyshe, Aaditya Ramdas, and Tom Mitchell.\n1299\t  Simultaneously uncovering the patterns of brain regions involved in different story reading sub-\n1300\t  processes. PLoS ONE, 9(11):e112575, 2014. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0112575.\n1301\t\n1302\tRoel M. Willems, Stefan L. Frank, Annabel D. Nijhof, Peter Hagoort, and Antal van den Bosch.\n1303\t Prediction during natural language comprehension. Cerebral Cortex, 26(6):2506–2516, 2016. doi:\n1304\t 10.1093/cercor/bhv075.\n1305\t\n1306\tFaxin Zhou, Siyuan Zhou, Yuhang Long, Adeen Flinker, and Chunming Lu. Hierarchical linguistic\n1307\t  predictions and cross-level information updating during narrative comprehension. Communica-\n1308\t  tions Biology, 9(107), 2026.\n1309\t\n1310\t\n1311\t\n1312\t\n1313\t                                                27\n1314\t\f                                         Appendix\n1315\t\n1316\t\n1317\tA     ROI Definitions and Correlations for Predictors\n1318\tAs shown in Figure 7, surprisal is lowly correlated with semantic relevance in both datasets. Specif-\n1319\tically, r = -0.18 Alice, r = -0.01 Moth, and these indicate that surprisal and semantic relevance\n1320\tare distinct metrics used in the present study.\n1321\t\n1322\t\n1323\t\n1324\t\n1325\t                     Figure 7: Correlations for predictors in the two datasets\n1326\t\n1327\t\n1328\t\n1329\tB    Robustness Analysis: Temporal Smoothness of Semantic Rele-\n1330\t     vance\n1331\tOne potential concern is that the semantic-relevance predictor may appear stronger than surprisal\n1332\tpartly because of its temporal structure. Since the BOLD signal is itself a slow, low-pass physio-\n1333\tlogical response, this raises an important alternative explanation: semantic relevance may predict\n1334\tBOLD more strongly not because it captures semantic integration, but because its temporal spec-\n1335\ttrum is better matched to BOLD.\n1336\t    To evaluate this possibility, we conducted three supplementary analyses. First, we compared\n1337\tthe temporal autocorrelation and spectral properties of semantic relevance and surprisal. Second,\n1338\twe smoothed surprisal to approximately match the lag-1 autocorrelation of semantic relevance\n1339\tand then reran the HRF-weighted 4–12 s FIR/deconvolution-style analysis. Third, we constructed\n1340\ttime-structure-preserving null predictors for semantic relevance using circular shifts, phase random-\n1341\tization, and block permutation within story/run structure.\n1342\t\n1343\t\n1344\t\n1345\t\n1346\t                                                 28\n1347\t\fB.1    Temporal autocorrelation and spectral properties\n1348\tFor each predictor, we computed the lag-1 autocorrelation, an autocorrelation-based effective tem-\n1349\tporal sample size, the proportion of power in the lowest 10% of the frequency range, and the spectral\n1350\tcentroid. The effective temporal sample size was computed as\n1351\t                                                      1 − r1\n1352\t                                          Neff = N           ,                                   (7)\n1353\t                                                      1 + r1\n1354\twhere r1 is the lag-1 autocorrelation. This value provides a simple index of the effective temporal\n1355\tdegrees of freedom after accounting for first-order autocorrelation.\n1356\t    These diagnostics confirm that semantic relevance is more temporally autocorrelated than sur-\n1357\tprisal and has relatively stronger low-frequency power. Thus, the smoothness concern is empirically\n1358\tvalid and should not be dismissed.\n1359\t\n1360\tB.2    Frequency-matched surprisal control\n1361\tWe next tested whether smoothing surprisal to match semantic relevance would make surprisal\n1362\tperform similarly. Surprisal was exponentially smoothed to approximate the lag-1 autocorrelation\n1363\tof semantic relevance. We then reran an HRF-weighted 4–12 s linear FIR approximation that\n1364\tcontrolled for the competing predictor, lagged lexical covariates, a polynomial time trend, and run\n1365\tfixed effects.\n1366\t    The smoothed-surprisal control did not reproduce the semantic-relevance effect. Although\n1367\tsmoothed surprisal was made similar to semantic relevance in lag-1 autocorrelation, it was not\n1368\tsignificant in any ROI after FDR correction. This result argues against the strongest version of the\n1369\tsmoothness-only explanation.\n1370\t\n1371\tB.3    Time-structure-preserving null predictors\n1372\tFinally, we replaced semantic relevance with surrogate predictors that preserved aspects of temporal\n1373\tstructure while disrupting the original word-to-BOLD alignment. We used three null procedures:\n1374\tcircular shift, phase randomization, and block permutation. Each procedure was applied within\n1375\tstory structure rather than by fully random global permutation. Each null method used 40 surro-\n1376\tgate repetitions per ROI. This number of repetitions gives only coarse empirical p values, with a\n1377\tminimum possible value of 1/(40 + 1) = .024. Thus, these tests should be interpreted as sensitivity\n1378\tanalyses rather than definitive permutation tests.\n1379\t    The surrogate analyses produced an important limitation on interpretation. The observed\n1380\tsemantic-relevance effects were not reproduced by frequency-matched surprisal, but the strict fami-\n1381\tlywise max-|t| surrogate tests did not reject the time-structure null. Moreover, the mean maximum\n1382\tabsolute t value under the surrogate distributions was larger than the observed maximum absolute\n1383\tt value for all three null methods. This means that the familywise surrogate results cannot be\n1384\ttreated merely as an underpowered positive trend; instead, they indicate that temporally struc-\n1385\ttured surrogate predictors can sometimes produce ROI-level maxima as large as, or larger than,\n1386\tthe observed effect. ROI-wise empirical tests provided limited local support in a small subset of\n1387\tROIs, but these effects were not broad enough to overturn the familywise null result.\n1388\t    In sum, these analyses support a narrower and more cautious interpretation. Semantic relevance\n1389\tis smoother and more low-frequency than surprisal, but the semantic-relevance advantage is not\n1390\texplained by simple lag-1 smoothing because frequency-matched surprisal did not yield comparable\n1391\teffects. However, the time-structure-preserving surrogate tests do not establish that the observed\n1392\t\n1393\t\n1394\t                                                 29\n1395\t\feffect is uniquely semantic rather than partly driven by temporally structured discourse-level varia-\n1396\ttion. We therefore treat this analysis as a robustness boundary. It weakens a pure smoothness-only\n1397\texplanation, but it does not provide a confirmatory semantic-specificity test. A stronger future\n1398\ttest should use substantially larger surrogate distributions, preregistered ROI-wise and familywise\n1399\tstatistics, cross-validated encoding models, and independently fixed semantic-relevance metrics to\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24218416-49cb-4659-887b-8543d119258d","uuid":"4d150218-ec71-4f0a-933f-5fe2c5e205fd","timestamp":"2026-07-20T08:00:23.231Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/paper_review/paper.txt","content":"                                                  19\n\flation may therefore explain why surprisal is significant in some datasets or brain regions but not\nconsistently across studies.\n    The present results therefore support a complementary-computation interpretation. They do\nnot show that prediction is unimportant, nor do they imply that semantic relevance replaces sur-\nprisal. Rather, they suggest that contextual semantic fit may be more robustly visible in slow BOLD\nresponses than local probabilistic error. This provides a possible bridge between psycholinguistic\ntheories of prediction and neurobiological accounts of semantic integration.\n\n4.4   Fast EEG responses and slow hemodynamic timescales\nAnother implication concerns the temporal scales at which lexical expectation and contextual se-\nmantic fit become detectable. Surprisal and predictability effects are well established in temporally\nprecise measures such as EEG and eye movements. In EEG, predictable or semantically fitting\nwords typically elicit reduced N400 amplitudes, linking contextual expectation and semantic ac-\ncess to neural responses within a few hundred milliseconds after word onset (Kutas and Hillyard,\n1984; Kutas and Federmeier, 2011; Lau et al., 2008; Frank et al., 2015). Eye-movement studies\nsimilarly show that word predictability and contextual constraint influence fixation durations and\nother reading behaviors during incremental comprehension (Rayner et al., 1996; Smith and Levy,\n2013; Sun et al., 2026).\n    A companion naturalistic-reading EEG analysis provides converging evidence (Sun and Wang,\n2026b). Across 22 participants and 32 channels, both semantic relevance and surprisal were asso-\nciated with N400 and P600 responses, but with partly distinguishable temporal profiles. Semantic\nrelevance showed broader effects in the N400 window, whereas surprisal exhibited comparatively\nstronger modulation around the P600 interval. The weak correlation between the two metrics in\nthat dataset further suggests that they capture partly distinct aspects of word-level processing.\n    These EEG results indicate that semantic relevance should not be understood exclusively as\na slow process. Recent ECoG evidence similarly shows that earlier and deeper language-model\nrepresentations correspond to earlier and later stages of cortical language processing, respectively\n(Goldstein et al., 2025). Computational measures differing in contextual depth may therefore be\nmost detectable at different neural timescales. Contextual semantic fit can influence neural activity\nwithin several hundred milliseconds, affecting both early semantic access or integration and later\nupdating or reanalysis. At the same time, EEG preserves rapid word-locked fluctuations that may\nbe attenuated in fMRI. BOLD responses are delayed and temporally smoothed (Boynton et al.,\n1996; Logothetis, 2003), and in continuous speech the hemodynamic responses elicited by adjacent\nwords overlap substantially. A brief and rapidly varying surprisal-related response may therefore\nbe difficult to isolate in BOLD, particularly after controlling for correlated lexical variables such as\nfrequency, word length, and duration.\n    Semantic relevance may be comparatively well aligned with the temporal characteristics of\nBOLD because it is computed from overlapping relations between each target word and its recent\ncontext. Although each estimate is word-specific, adjacent estimates share contextual information\nand may track semantic structure that evolves continuously over several words. Such temporally\nextended contextual variation may survive hemodynamic smoothing more readily than highly local\nfluctuations in probabilistic unexpectedness. This interpretation is compatible with evidence for\nhierarchical temporal receptive windows across cortex, whereby early auditory and language regions\nrespond to relatively short-timescale information, whereas higher-order temporal, parietal, and\ndefault-mode regions integrate information over longer periods during naturalistic comprehension\n(Hasson et al., 2008; Lerner et al., 2011; Hasson et al., 2015). Chang et al. (2022) further showed\nthat information during narrative comprehension propagates across this cortical timescale hierarchy,\n\n\n                                                  20\n\fproviding a systems-level framework for understanding why context-sensitive semantic variables\nmay be expressed as delayed and spatially distributed BOLD responses.\n    In sum, the EEG and fMRI findings suggest a difference in measurement sensitivity rather than\na strict separation between fast and slow linguistic computations. Both surprisal and semantic\nrelevance can modulate rapid EEG responses, but semantic relevance may also generate temporally\nsustained variation that is more readily detectable in the slow BOLD signal. Surprisal-related\nBOLD effects may therefore be more dependent on stimulus structure, language-model specification,\ntemporal alignment, and the control variables included in the analysis.\n\n4.5   Naturalistic semantic networks and situation-model updating\nThe use of naturalistic spoken narratives is central to the present study. Real story comprehension\nrequires listeners to maintain and update characters, events, goals, causal relations, and discourse\ncontext over time. Naturalistic fMRI studies have shown that semantic information is represented\nacross distributed cortical systems rather than being confined to classical language areas (Huth\net al., 2016; Wehbe et al., 2014; Jain and Huth, 2018). This broader organization makes naturalistic\ndatasets especially useful for testing predictors related to contextual semantic fit.\n    Semantic relevance may therefore relate to a distributed comprehension network. The present\nROI-level results are broadly consistent with this view but also reveal an informative gradient. In\nthe Moth dataset, the strongest semantic relevance effects were observed in CG, ACC, vmPFC,\nand PCUN (these regions associated with cognitive control, contextual integration, and situation-\nmodel construction ) rather than in classical perisylvian language areas such as STG, MTG, or IFG,\nwhich showed weaker (though still significant) effects. This pattern is consistent with the idea that\nsemantic relevance primarily indexes discourse-level contextual fit and situation-model updating\n(Ferstl et al., 2008), rather than lower-level lexical-semantic access. In Alice, by contrast, the\nstrongest FIR effects were in STG and MTG, possibly reflecting the stronger temporal alignment\nand stimulus control in that dataset. These regional differences across datasets underscore the\nneed for future voxel-wise analyses that can more precisely localize the neural sources of semantic\nrelevance effects (Binder and Desai, 2011; Lambon Ralph et al., 2017; Seghier, 2013).\n    At the same time, widespread effects should be interpreted cautiously. Broad ROI-level sig-\nnificance, especially in the Moth dataset, does not imply that all regions encode semantic rele-\nvance in the same way. Some effects may reflect core semantic processing, whereas others may\nreflect attention, memory, narrative structure, global temporal dynamics, or unmodeled acoustic\nand discourse-level covariates. The safe conclusion is that semantic relevance tracks a naturalistic\ncomprehension signal that plausibly relates to contextual semantic integration and situation-model\nupdating, but future work should use nuisance controls, temporal surrogate analyses, and held-\nout encoding models to determine which components of this distributed response are specifically\nsemantic.\n\n4.6   Methodological implications\nThe results have broader implications for computational neuroscience of language. Computational\npredictors should not be treated as interchangeable regressors simply because they are derived from\nthe same words. Surprisal and semantic relevance make different claims about neural computation.\nSurprisal indexes local probabilistic unexpectedness, whereas semantic relevance indexes contextual\nsemantic fit and integration. These computations may operate over partly different timescales and\nmay therefore require different statistical models.\n    Recent work has demonstrated that GPT-based encoding models can predict sentence-level\n\n\n                                                 21\n\fresponses in the human language network and can identify novel sentences that reliably drive or\nsuppress its activity, with surprisal and linguistic well-formedness emerging as important determi-\nnants of response strength (Tuckute et al., 2024). These findings illustrate the power of computa-\ntional representations for predicting and manipulating neural responses to language. Nevertheless,\nsuccessful brain prediction by a computational representation does not by itself establish that the\nbrain implements the model’s training objective or computational mechanism (Antonello and Huth,\n2024). Accordingly, the stronger association between semantic relevance and BOLD in the present\nanalyses should be interpreted as evidence for the neural sensitivity of the metric, rather than as\nproof that the brain explicitly computes semantic relevance in the precise form implemented here.\n    The complementary use of GAMMs and FIR/deconvolution is important for this reason. GAMMs\napplied to transformed or HRF-convolved BOLD are useful for testing nonlinear predictor-response\nrelationships while controlling lexical and subject-level variability. FIR/deconvolution applied to\noriginal continuous BOLD is useful for estimating the delayed response profile without forcing a\nsingle canonical HRF shape. In short, these methods allow one to ask both whether a predictor\nexplains BOLD variance and when its effect emerges after word onset. This issue is especially\nimportant because BOLD is a low-pass signal and semantic relevance is itself temporally smoother\nthan surprisal.\n    Recent work has introduced methods for estimating semantic relevance and shown that these\nmetrics predict eye movements during reading across multiple languages (Sun and Liu, 2024; Sun\net al., 2026). Related studies further suggest that semantic relevance may contribute to modeling\nspeech production, spontaneous speech characteristics, EEG responses, and visual attention (Sun\nand Wang, 2026c,b,a). The present study extends this line of research by demonstrating that\nsemantic relevance also predicts BOLD responses during language comprehension.\n    In spite of these, several limitations should be considered. As semantic relevance is temporally\nsmoother than surprisal, some effects may reflect better alignment with BOLD’s low-frequency\nstructure rather than semantic processing alone. In addition, unmodeled factors such as acoustic\nproperties, speech rate, story progression, motion, scanner drift, global signal, and temporal au-\ntocorrelation may contribute to the observed effects. The Moth dataset also included only eight\nparticipants, limiting group-level generalizability despite its rich within-participant data. Finally,\nthe fMRI findings are related to companion EEG evidence only at the interpretive level rather than\nthrough a joint cross-modal analysis.\n\n\n5    Conclusion\nAcross two naturalistic fMRI datasets, semantic relevance was associated with BOLD responses\nduring spoken-language comprehension, whereas surprisal showed weaker and less consistent effects\nin these ROI-level analyses. These findings suggest that contextual semantic fit may be more readily\nexpressed in slow hemodynamic responses than local word-level unexpectedness. The contribution\nof semantic relevance to computational neuroscience is that it provides a computable bridge between\nword-level language models and slower neural dynamics measured with fMRI. Unlike surprisal,\nwhich captures forward prediction error, semantic relevance quantifies how an incoming word fits\ninto the recent semantic context, making it useful for modeling sustained integration processes that\nunfold across discourse and engage distributed cortical systems.\n    This distinction links different computational descriptions of language to different neural mea-\nsurement timescales. Surprisal may primarily capture fast prediction-related processing, whereas\nsemantic relevance may capture more sustained contextual integration that is better matched to the\ntemporal dynamics of BOLD. More broadly, the results argue that models of naturalistic language\n\n\n                                                 22\n\fcomprehension should move beyond forward prediction alone and explicitly incorporate contextual\ncoherence, semantic fit, and discourse-level integration as core components of neural language pro-\ncessing. Semantic relevance may therefore provide a useful bridge between computational models\nof lexical processing and neural systems supporting semantic integration, narrative comprehension,\nand situation-model updating.\n\n\nData and Code Availability\nAll analyses were conducted using publicly available fMRI datasets. The Alice data were obtained\nfrom the Alice dataset release, and the Moth data were obtained from the natural language fMRI\ndataset for voxelwise encoding models. Analysis scripts, intermediate result tables, and generated\nfigures are currently stored in the local project directory. The public repository is available at: .\n\n\nAcknowledgments\nWe thank the creators of the Alice and Moth datasets for making their naturalistic fMRI resources\npublicly available.\n\n\nReferences\nRichard Antonello and Alexander Huth. Predictive coding or just feature discovery? an alternative\n  account of why language models fit brain data. Neurobiology of Language, 5(1):64–79, 2024.\nShohini Bhattasali, Jonathan R. Brennan, Wen-Ming Luh, Berta Franzluebbers, and John T. Hale.\n  The alice datasets: fmri & eeg observations of natural language comprehension. In Proceedings\n  of the 12th Conference on Language Resources and Evaluation (LREC 2020), pages 120–125.\n  European Language Resources Association, 2020.\nJeffrey R. Binder and Rutvik H. Desai. The neurobiology of semantic memory. Trends in Cognitive\n  Sciences, 15(11):527–536, 2011.\nGeoffrey M. Boynton, Stephen A. Engel, Gary H. Glover, and David J. Heeger. Linear systems\n analysis of functional magnetic resonance imaging in human v1. Journal of Neuroscience, 16(13):\